00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:56.120
Now, today's topic
is urgent and timely.

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:59.300
Our panelists will offer
insight into the science

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:01.760
and the social roots
behind the epidemics

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:04.370
that we read about
on a regular basis,

00:03:04.370 --> 00:03:09.680
from Ebola, Zika, HIV/AIDS,
malaria, and Lyme disease,

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:13.940
to gun violence, opioid
addiction, and depression.

00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:18.440
We all come to this subject
with our own perspective.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:21.200
As an historian,
my orientation is

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:25.670
to locate events in the larger
social and historical context

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:27.590
in which they arise.

00:03:27.590 --> 00:03:31.550
Whether an epidemic unfolds
during China's Tang dynasty

00:03:31.550 --> 00:03:35.930
or amid preparations for the
Rio Olympics just last year,

00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:39.710
a society's response to
a fast-spreading illness

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:43.280
is shaped not just by the
capabilities and limitations

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:46.550
of medical science at that
particular moment in time,

00:03:46.550 --> 00:03:50.460
but also by complex social
factors such as race,

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:53.180
class, gender, and religion.

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:57.320
For an historian, epidemics
can provide a revealing window

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:01.010
into a society at a
particular moment in history.

00:04:01.010 --> 00:04:04.280
Let me give you one example
from our own backyard here

00:04:04.280 --> 00:04:10.370
in Boston, the smallpox
epidemic in Boston of 1721.

00:04:10.370 --> 00:04:13.820
By the 1700s,
smallpox inoculation

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:17.269
had been practiced for
centuries in parts of Africa,

00:04:17.269 --> 00:04:20.120
as well as in
China and in India.

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:22.940
In colonial Boston,
however, the practice

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:25.220
was virtually unheard of.

00:04:25.220 --> 00:04:29.270
That changed when an enslaved
man, called Onesimus,

00:04:29.270 --> 00:04:32.360
told the Puritan religious
leader, Cotton Mather,

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:36.740
about a practice common among
his tribe in North Africa,

00:04:36.740 --> 00:04:40.190
a procedure that protected
him against smallpox, leaving

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:43.190
only a small scar on his arm.

00:04:43.190 --> 00:04:46.280
A few years later, when
a smallpox epidemic

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:49.850
broke out in Boston
in 1721, Mather

00:04:49.850 --> 00:04:52.370
recalled Onesimus's words.

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:56.660
And he became an outspoken
advocate for inoculation.

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:00.080
Many white Christians
in Boston mocked Mather

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:03.410
for relying on the
testimony of an enslaved man

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:07.730
and denounced inoculation for
its roots in Africa and Asia,

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:10.280
calling it a heathen practice.

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:13.310
Other Bostonians simply
rejected the idea

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:17.600
of deliberately infecting
healthy people with a disease.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:21.020
By August of 1721,
the controversy

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:24.500
had become so heated that
someone threw a grenade

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:26.180
through Mather's window.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:28.250
The grenade didn't
detonate, but Mather

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:30.590
found a note attached
to it, which read,

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:35.050
and I quote, "I'll inoculate you
with this with a pox to you,"

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:36.440
end quote.

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:39.650
A few Bostonians did
support immunizations,

00:05:39.650 --> 00:05:42.980
including Dr.
Zabdiel Boylston, who

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:46.340
would go on to perform
America's first inoculations

00:05:46.340 --> 00:05:50.030
on his own child and
two enslaved people.

00:05:50.030 --> 00:05:53.550
But Mather's appeals
were largely ignored.

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:56.150
Smallpox spread unchecked.

00:05:56.150 --> 00:06:00.470
And by the end of the
epidemic in 1722, over half

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:03.650
of Boston's population
had fallen ill.

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:06.090
More than 800 died.

00:06:06.090 --> 00:06:08.880
The story of Boston's
smallpox outbreak

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:12.810
reveals much more than
the spread of a pathogen.

00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:16.590
It is a story about racial
prejudices in colonial New

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:20.520
England, about the rigidities
of Boston's society,

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:22.740
and about the
forgotten contributions

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:26.850
of enslaved Africans to
American medical practice.

00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:29.550
Still today, how
epidemics unfold around

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:33.150
the world is shaped by
complicated interactions

00:06:33.150 --> 00:06:36.540
between medical advancements
and the social and political

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:39.720
factors that inform
and complicate

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:42.410
the work of epidemiology.

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:45.260
50 years ago, many
scientists considered

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:48.740
the age of infectious
disease to be over.

00:06:48.740 --> 00:06:51.320
The rise of antibiotics
and vaccines

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:54.800
was considered a triumph
of modern medicine.

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:57.440
But today, diseases
we thought were gone

00:06:57.440 --> 00:06:59.270
seem to be reappearing.

00:06:59.270 --> 00:07:01.490
For example, mumps
went from being

00:07:01.490 --> 00:07:05.000
common to being unheard
of after the introduction

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.900
of the measles, mumps, and
rubella vaccine in 1971.

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:13.370
But it has returned to Harvard
and elsewhere in recent years.

00:07:13.370 --> 00:07:16.550
Other contagious diseases
are also on the rise,

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:20.000
thanks in part to globalization
and global travel,

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:25.010
environmental change, population
growth, and many other factors.

00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:29.480
In addition, we are increasingly
aware of non-infectious disease

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:33.380
epidemics, often with
complicated social roots.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:36.800
We will explore these topics
during our afternoon session

00:07:36.800 --> 00:07:42.290
today with experts on guns,
