00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:08.810
and give you some context
for our young science

00:10:08.810 --> 00:10:11.540
of epidemiology.

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:14.210
Chances are when you
think of epidemics,

00:10:14.210 --> 00:10:16.220
you think of infectious disease.

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:18.950
And indeed, you'd be correct
that the roots of epidemiology

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:22.220
lie in concerns about diseases
like the bubonic plague,

00:10:22.220 --> 00:10:24.200
cholera, and the flu.

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:26.240
These diseases
have long captured

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:28.520
our imagination and our fears.

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:31.970
Here is a 17th century
painting by Flemish artist,

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:36.530
Michael Sweerts of one of the
first epidemics ever recorded

00:10:36.530 --> 00:10:37.640
in history.

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:41.390
The date is 430 BC,
and we're in Athens,

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:43.880
in the middle of the
Peloponnesian War.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:46.610
1/3 to 2/3 of the
city of Athens was

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:48.860
struck by a strange disease.

00:10:48.860 --> 00:10:51.440
And most who became ill died.

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:53.960
Thucydides, the
historian, himself

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:55.790
survived to describe
the epidemic,

00:10:55.790 --> 00:10:58.670
a disease so severe and
deadly that no one could

00:10:58.670 --> 00:11:00.940
recall anywhere it's like.

00:11:00.940 --> 00:11:03.200
And naive physicians were
the first to contract

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:06.420
the disease due to their
contact with the sick.

00:11:06.420 --> 00:11:10.030
Thucydides recounted tales of
terrifying social upheaval,

00:11:10.030 --> 00:11:12.160
of the disappearance
of social morals,

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:15.100
because people felt they were
living under a death sentence.

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:17.950
Citizens started spending
money indiscriminately.

00:11:17.950 --> 00:11:19.690
Plus, some of the
poor, he noted,

00:11:19.690 --> 00:11:22.300
unexpectedly became wealthy
by inheriting the property

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:23.580
of their relatives.

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:25.570
Got to watch out for
those nouveau riche.

00:11:25.570 --> 00:11:27.394
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:32.410
In fact, the disease
changed history.

00:11:32.410 --> 00:11:35.080
Although the Spartans,
seeing the funeral pyres

00:11:35.080 --> 00:11:37.810
burning in Athens,
retreated rather than

00:11:37.810 --> 00:11:39.580
come in contact
with the disease,

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:41.520
Athens itself was weakened.

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:43.960
Pericles, the general,
succumbed, and was followed

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:45.920
by a series of weak leaders.

00:11:45.920 --> 00:11:50.000
The next offensive Athens
launched was a disaster.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.940
But Thucydides was
no epidemiologist.

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:56.600
So the cause of the plague
of Athens was, and still is,

00:11:56.600 --> 00:11:57.980
a medical mystery.

00:11:57.980 --> 00:12:00.920
Epidemiologists today debate
what caused the epidemic,

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:02.720
whether it was the
bubonic plague,

00:12:02.720 --> 00:12:05.040
typhoid fever, or
perhaps even Ebola.

00:12:07.650 --> 00:12:10.050
It wasn't until the
mid-18th century

00:12:10.050 --> 00:12:13.620
before Westerners began to take
a systematic look at epidemics.

00:12:13.620 --> 00:12:16.290
John Graunt, here, the
son of a London draper,

00:12:16.290 --> 00:12:18.989
had a native curiosity and
a knack for statistics,

00:12:18.989 --> 00:12:21.030
and made his way into the
Fellowship of the Royal

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:23.370
Society.

00:12:23.370 --> 00:12:27.110
He published the first analyses
of the bills of mortality,

00:12:27.110 --> 00:12:28.890
London's death registry.

00:12:28.890 --> 00:12:34.440
Here's what he recorded for
December 1742 to December 1743.

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:39.750
The leading causes of death, you
can see here, are convulsions,

00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:42.270
which I'm wondering if
that might be heart disease

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:46.170
because it's so prevalent;
consumption, which, of course,

00:12:46.170 --> 00:12:49.980
we know of as tuberculosis--
see if I can see this here--

00:12:49.980 --> 00:12:56.320
fever, no surprise,
old age, smallpox--

00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:59.440
they apparently hadn't
heard of the vaccine yet--

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:02.240
and, horribly, teeth.

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:05.740
I think that must be a
terrible way to go, frankly.

00:13:05.740 --> 00:13:08.800
Conspicuously absent are our
modern diseases-- cancer,

00:13:08.800 --> 00:13:12.500
only 61 deaths, and
diabetes, one death.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:14.604
In fact, you were more
likely to die from evil

00:13:14.604 --> 00:13:15.770
than you were from diabetes.

00:13:15.770 --> 00:13:19.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:19.930 --> 00:13:23.480
Some exotic
diseases, including--

00:13:23.480 --> 00:13:25.130
I can't read that from here--

00:13:25.130 --> 00:13:29.410
headmold shot, horseshoe
head, and water in the head.

00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:32.097
And my favorite, I
think the only way to go

00:13:32.097 --> 00:13:33.180
is a rising of the lights.

00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:36.404
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:37.890 --> 00:13:40.500
John Graunt made these
lists in an attempt

00:13:40.500 --> 00:13:43.380
to predict waves of the
plague, which he didn't quite

00:13:43.380 --> 00:13:44.430
manage to do.

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:46.470
But he's the father of
the most fundamental

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:49.590
of epidemiologic tasks,
the classification

00:13:49.590 --> 00:13:53.290
and counting of disease.

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:55.690
Some hundred years later
in London, John Graunt

00:13:55.690 --> 00:13:58.760
would be followed by one
John Snow, a physician.

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:00.850
Now, the epidemiologists
in the audience

00:14:00.850 --> 00:14:03.160
would be permitted
a collective groan

00:14:03.160 --> 00:14:05.920
because this story is the
equivalent of our Washington

00:14:05.920 --> 00:14:08.050
and the cherry trees.

00:14:08.050 --> 00:14:10.990
This is our first known
use of medical statistics

00:14:10.990 --> 00:14:13.690
to actually resolve the
cause of an epidemic.

00:14:13.690 --> 00:14:16.810
It focuses on a particular
neighborhood of London

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:20.530
which was experiencing
an outbreak of cholera.

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:22.840
At the time, the advice
of the Medical Council

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:25.450
was to avoid vegetables
and unripe fruit

00:14:25.450 --> 00:14:29.680
and to abstain from cold water
when heated and ardent spirits,

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:33.080
unless, of course, habit
made that impossible.

00:14:33.080 --> 00:14:35.647
In fact, boiled water
and ardent spirits

00:14:35.647 --> 00:14:37.480
may have been the safest
beverages in London

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:40.100
to drink at the time.

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:44.150
But the prevailing theory
among the people of London

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:47.210
was that cholera arose
from miasma, or vapors

00:14:47.210 --> 00:14:48.710
from the Thames.

00:14:48.710 --> 00:14:50.960
This is 1854 London.

00:14:50.960 --> 00:14:52.610
And although the
concept of germ theory

00:14:52.610 --> 00:14:56.240
had been proposed by Wu Youke
at the turn of the 16th century

00:14:56.240 --> 00:14:59.510
in Ming Dynasty
China, in 1854 London,

00:14:59.510 --> 00:15:01.850
the germ theory of
disease wouldn't grab hold

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:04.670
for another 50 years.

00:15:04.670 --> 00:15:07.250
John Snow took it
upon himself to obtain

00:15:07.250 --> 00:15:10.400
a map of the effected district
and to plot every cholera death

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:11.660
on that map.

00:15:11.660 --> 00:15:14.300
This is what we call
shoe-leather epidemiology,

00:15:14.300 --> 00:15:17.570
the close, geographic
investigation of outbreaks.

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:19.940
The basic principle of
shoe-leather epidemiology

00:15:19.940 --> 00:15:21.680
is one we still
use, whether we're

00:15:21.680 --> 00:15:24.770
tracing syphilis contacts,
the spread of Ebola,

00:15:24.770 --> 00:15:27.060
or investigating the
quintessential foodborne

00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:31.010
illness we classically call
the church picnic problem.

00:15:31.010 --> 00:15:34.250
John Snow went one step further
than just mapping the cases.

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:37.220
He also mapped the lines that
supplied London's drinking

00:15:37.220 --> 00:15:39.484
water through
neighborhood pumps.

00:15:39.484 --> 00:15:41.150
There were two companies
supplying water

00:15:41.150 --> 00:15:42.380
to the neighborhood.

00:15:42.380 --> 00:15:44.510
The Lambeth Waterworks,
here in blue,

00:15:44.510 --> 00:15:47.780
drew its water upstream from
the London sewage effluent

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:50.000
in the Thames, while the
Southwark and Vauxhall

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:54.020
Company, shown here in gold,
drew its water downstream

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:55.580
from the Thames sewage.

00:15:55.580 --> 00:15:57.830
Snow traced the source
of cholera to the latter,

00:15:57.830 --> 00:16:01.550
and in particular, to a
hand pump on Broad Street.

00:16:01.550 --> 00:16:04.132
Now, you might ask
about the women

00:16:04.132 --> 00:16:06.590
who died from cholera-- those
who lived next door to a pump

00:16:06.590 --> 00:16:08.480
from the cleaner Lambeth line.

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:11.270
Turns out she had just moved
there from Broad Street

00:16:11.270 --> 00:16:13.972
and sent for water daily from
the old Broad Street pump

00:16:13.972 --> 00:16:15.305
because she preferred its taste.

00:16:18.090 --> 00:16:22.050
Famously, John Snow removed the
handle of the Broad Street pump

00:16:22.050 --> 00:16:23.640
and cured London of cholera.

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:25.560
He's considered
by most Westerners

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:28.610
to be the father of
modern epidemiology.

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:31.240
Here is a map of modern London.

00:16:31.240 --> 00:16:34.280
And you could still visit
the old Broad Street pump--

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:35.810
it's now Broadwick Street--

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:38.900
which is located right between
the Anthropologie store

00:16:38.900 --> 00:16:40.430
and Chipotle Mexican Grill.

00:16:40.430 --> 00:16:43.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:47.142
But the second greatest
plague the world has ever

00:16:47.142 --> 00:16:49.100
known-- the first was
actually the Black Death,

00:16:49.100 --> 00:16:52.580
the plague itself, bubonic
plague in the 14th century.

00:16:52.580 --> 00:16:56.780
The second greatest plague
is the influenza of 1918,

00:16:56.780 --> 00:17:00.170
also known as the Spanish flu
It swept the globe, infecting

00:17:00.170 --> 00:17:03.500
nearly a third of all people
and killing between 20 and 50

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:07.400
million, more than died
in all of World War I.

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:09.859
Downton Abbey fans
will recall that

00:17:09.859 --> 00:17:13.040
the Spanish flu with the
demise of Miss Lavinia Swire.

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:15.770
Critics of the show complained
that the entire household

00:17:15.770 --> 00:17:18.200
of Lord Grantham would
have been gripped in fear

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:19.480
of catching the disease.

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:21.440
And dear Matthew
would probably not

00:17:21.440 --> 00:17:23.599
have been quite as
attentive as pictured here.

00:17:23.599 --> 00:17:25.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:25.670 --> 00:17:29.630
In fact, the decline of
infectious disease mortality

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:31.940
due to the advent of
antibiotics and vaccines

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:34.550
in the mid-20th century
is one of public health's

00:17:34.550 --> 00:17:36.110
great triumphs.

00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:39.620
You can see here that
diphtheria, typhoid,

00:17:39.620 --> 00:17:42.080
and whooping cough,
also known as pertussis,

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:45.860
declined quickly due to the
DPT vaccine we give children.

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:48.500
Measles, too, is
prevented by vaccine,

00:17:48.500 --> 00:17:52.620
and scarlet fever is
treated by antibiotics.

00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:54.950
But we are still in
the grip of contagion,

00:17:54.950 --> 00:17:58.340
including some new diseases
and modern causes of mortality.

00:17:58.340 --> 00:18:01.590
Can anyone guess
which one this is?

00:18:01.590 --> 00:18:02.840
Feel free to call out.

00:18:02.840 --> 00:18:03.660
And if you have a--

00:18:03.660 --> 00:18:04.159
Zika.

00:18:04.159 --> 00:18:04.920
Very good.

00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:05.970
This is Zika.

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:07.830
We'll be hearing today
about the Zika virus

00:18:07.830 --> 00:18:11.670
from Dr. Celina Turchi
Martelli in the first panel.

00:18:11.670 --> 00:18:13.479
How about this one?

00:18:13.479 --> 00:18:15.270
No fair calling it out
if you have funding.

00:18:15.270 --> 00:18:16.230
- Lyme.

00:18:16.230 --> 00:18:18.470
- Lyme, exactly.

00:18:18.470 --> 00:18:19.550
Lyme disease.

00:18:19.550 --> 00:18:21.560
Dr. Kevin Esfelt
of MIT will tell us

00:18:21.560 --> 00:18:25.150
about Lyme and some
provocative ways to combat it.

00:18:25.150 --> 00:18:28.850
This one, which
has local issues--

00:18:28.850 --> 00:18:32.750
here is our dear commonwealth
2011 to 2013, 2014

00:18:32.750 --> 00:18:35.090
to 2016-- exactly, opiates.

00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:38.790
These are deaths
from drug overdose.

00:18:38.790 --> 00:18:40.290
We'll be talking about that.

00:18:40.290 --> 00:18:43.170
Dr. Andrew Kolodny will
join us in the afternoon

00:18:43.170 --> 00:18:47.240
in a session devoted to
epidemics with social roots.

00:18:47.240 --> 00:18:47.800
And this one.

00:18:52.165 --> 00:18:52.790
- Gun violence.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:54.050
- Good guess, gun violence.

00:18:54.050 --> 00:18:55.150
This his gun ownership.

00:18:55.150 --> 00:19:00.430
But owning a gun does not mean
you will be injured by a gun.

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:03.820
Here, you can see homicides by
firearms per 1 million people.

00:19:03.820 --> 00:19:06.820
We really-- oh, bad choice
of words-- trump everybody

00:19:06.820 --> 00:19:09.620
else in this arena.

00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:12.490
Dr. Andrew Papachristos,
a sociologist from Yale,

00:19:12.490 --> 00:19:15.340
will address the application
of epidemiologic principles

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:19.300
to understand and combat
the spread of gun violence.

00:19:19.300 --> 00:19:23.200
The good news is that we have
new tools as epidemiologists.

00:19:23.200 --> 00:19:26.090
Through our understandings
of pathogens and DNA,

00:19:26.090 --> 00:19:29.380
we now use techniques with names
like molecular epidemiology

00:19:29.380 --> 00:19:31.630
and genetic epidemiology,
about which you'll

00:19:31.630 --> 00:19:33.460
hear throughout the day.

00:19:33.460 --> 00:19:36.160
We also have new
techniques of manipulating

00:19:36.160 --> 00:19:40.360
the genome of disease vectors
like mosquitoes and mice.

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:43.510
You'll hear about the concept
of gene drive before lunch.

00:19:43.510 --> 00:19:46.070
And after lunch,
the panel will--

00:19:46.070 --> 00:19:49.720
well, after lunch, a panel
will address the exciting gains

00:19:49.720 --> 00:19:51.640
and the analytic
challenges of big data

00:19:51.640 --> 00:19:55.420
epidemiology, where everything
from the legions of bacteria

00:19:55.420 --> 00:19:58.930
in the microbiome of your
gut to cell phone records

00:19:58.930 --> 00:20:01.690
can be used to trace,
understand, and predict

00:20:01.690 --> 00:20:03.680
epidemics.

00:20:03.680 --> 00:20:05.770
We'll also discuss
the tension between

00:20:05.770 --> 00:20:09.190
private and public sector
data and the concept

00:20:09.190 --> 00:20:10.909
of open science.

00:20:10.909 --> 00:20:12.700
At the end of the day,
our keynote speaker,

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:14.860
Laurie Garrett, author
of The Coming Plague

00:20:14.860 --> 00:20:17.080
and member of the Council
on Foreign Relations,

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:19.510
will address the role of
international politics,

00:20:19.510 --> 00:20:25.180
of globalization and isolation
in the role of countries

00:20:25.180 --> 00:20:28.000
responding to epidemics.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.940
This is CDC's list of
the top 10 public health

00:20:30.940 --> 00:20:32.880
victories of the 20th century.

00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:36.040
Epidemiology, the young
science, played a central role

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:37.940
in achieving all 10 of them.

00:20:37.940 --> 00:20:41.051
After all, epidemiology is
the science of public health,

00:20:41.051 --> 00:20:42.550
whether we're talking
about diseases

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:47.290
caused by pathogens or diseases
with pathogenic social causes.

00:20:47.290 --> 00:20:49.540
I'm excited about the chance
to learn about the coming

00:20:49.540 --> 00:20:52.990
challenges, and hopefully
victories, of epidemiology

00:20:52.990 --> 00:20:55.500
in the 21st century.

00:20:55.500 --> 00:20:57.900
And now, it's my pleasure
to invite our first panel

00:20:57.900 --> 00:20:59.380
to the stage.

00:20:59.380 --> 00:21:00.630
Why don't you guys come on up?

00:21:00.630 --> 00:21:03.582
And I will introduce to
you Dr. Marcia Castro.

00:21:03.582 --> 00:21:05.040
Throughout the day,
we'll just give

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:06.210
really quick introductions.

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:09.960
You've got in your program
full bios for each speaker.

00:21:09.960 --> 00:21:11.784
So, Marcia Castro is
an Associate Professor

00:21:11.784 --> 00:21:13.200
in the Department
of Global Health

00:21:13.200 --> 00:21:17.070
and Population at the Harvard
TH Chan School of Public Health,

00:21:17.070 --> 00:21:19.650
and a Faculty Associate
at the Harvard University

00:21:19.650 --> 00:21:21.580
Center for the Environment.

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:24.270
She's published extensively on
the epidemiology and control

00:21:24.270 --> 00:21:27.420
of infectious diseases,
environment and health,

00:21:27.420 --> 00:21:30.600
spatial methods, and health,
particularly in Brazil.

00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:32.868
Please join me in
welcoming Marcia Castro.

00:21:32.868 --> 00:21:36.186
