00:21:41.040 --> 00:21:42.570
Good morning, everybody.

00:21:42.570 --> 00:21:45.570
Once again, thank you so
much for putting together

00:21:45.570 --> 00:21:49.210
an event with such an
incredible and important topic.

00:21:49.210 --> 00:21:51.420
And our first panel
we will go straight

00:21:51.420 --> 00:21:55.600
into infectious diseases in
this new era of epidemics.

00:21:55.600 --> 00:21:58.590
And I think what really makes
it a new era is that we're not

00:21:58.590 --> 00:22:02.060
discussing anymore of if we're
going to have another outbreak.

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:02.970
We know we will.

00:22:02.970 --> 00:22:05.520
It's just a matter of
when and what pathogen is

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:07.730
going to be this new outbreak.

00:22:07.730 --> 00:22:11.040
We live in a time that
everything moves faster--

00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:15.500
people, information,
goods, but also pathogens.

00:22:15.500 --> 00:22:17.580
And that makes it
really challenge when

00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:19.560
we have one of those outbreaks.

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:23.370
And in the very first
moment of an epidemic when

00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:26.560
cases are going up and
everything is under chaos,

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:29.280
we have many challenges
that we have to address.

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:30.970
How do you find those cases?

00:22:30.970 --> 00:22:32.190
How do you contain?

00:22:32.190 --> 00:22:34.980
Do you have tools to
be able to treat them?

00:22:34.980 --> 00:22:36.780
How do you deliver
this treatment?

00:22:36.780 --> 00:22:39.360
Do you have health systems
that are strong enough

00:22:39.360 --> 00:22:42.240
to be able to be in the
field finding the people

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:45.270
and delivering the response?

00:22:45.270 --> 00:22:47.280
We can't forget
all the challenges

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:51.000
of blending the different
institutions in the government.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:54.720
But also different bodies,
national and international--

00:22:54.720 --> 00:22:58.330
they're going to be in the field
of responding to this epidemic.

00:22:58.330 --> 00:23:01.560
Let's not forget also
about the ethical

00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:05.580
and the legal challenges
in prioritizing responses

00:23:05.580 --> 00:23:09.190
depending on the epidemic
we are talking about.

00:23:09.190 --> 00:23:13.080
So there are also another
phase that comes afterwards,

00:23:13.080 --> 00:23:17.130
which is when people basically
say the outbreak is over,

00:23:17.130 --> 00:23:20.490
which raises the
question, when is it over?

00:23:20.490 --> 00:23:22.290
Is it ever over?

00:23:22.290 --> 00:23:23.820
Which is an important one--

00:23:23.820 --> 00:23:27.610
tends to be neglected, which
is to look at the aftermath.

00:23:27.610 --> 00:23:31.500
So what happens after
the epidemic is not

00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:33.120
in the spotlight anymore?

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:34.600
What are the consequences?

00:23:34.600 --> 00:23:36.690
What are the sequela
of the disease?

00:23:36.690 --> 00:23:40.380
But above all, let's look
at the social, the economic,

00:23:40.380 --> 00:23:44.910
and the broad, demographic
impacts of the epidemic.

00:23:44.910 --> 00:23:47.290
We don't have much
attention to that,

00:23:47.290 --> 00:23:50.370
but we are lucky that we do
have some research groups that

00:23:50.370 --> 00:23:52.950
stay on the ground and
try to bring information

00:23:52.950 --> 00:23:56.340
about this aftermath when
everybody thinks it's over,

00:23:56.340 --> 00:23:58.740
but we're not quite there yet.

00:23:58.740 --> 00:24:02.070
So, our panel has
three stellar speakers

00:24:02.070 --> 00:24:04.020
that will talk a
little bit about this.

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:06.740
I'm not going to read their
bios you have in your program.

00:24:06.740 --> 00:24:09.120
And you should read
because they are terrific.

00:24:09.120 --> 00:24:11.550
But I'll give you
an overview of what

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:14.109
they are going to touch
upon in those issues

00:24:14.109 --> 00:24:15.150
that I briefly mentioned.

00:24:15.150 --> 00:24:18.780
So, we're going to start
with Dr. Christian Happi.

00:24:18.780 --> 00:24:23.580
And he's going to bring how this
top-notch technology that we

00:24:23.580 --> 00:24:26.430
have now can help us
in those epidemics.

00:24:26.430 --> 00:24:28.980
So, he's going to talk
about how genomics

00:24:28.980 --> 00:24:32.940
can be used for
pathogen discovery,

00:24:32.940 --> 00:24:35.430
but also for surveillance.

00:24:35.430 --> 00:24:38.250
Then we're going to move
to Dr. Anne Rimoin, who

00:24:38.250 --> 00:24:40.030
has one of those
research groups that

00:24:40.030 --> 00:24:43.350
actually stay on the ground when
everybody is saying, it's over.

00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:47.310
And she's going to talk to
us about her phenomenal work

00:24:47.310 --> 00:24:52.560
of tracking the survivors of the
1976 Ebola outbreak in the DRC

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:55.620
and share with us
some of the findings

00:24:55.620 --> 00:24:59.910
that she had about the
long-term effects of the Ebola

00:24:59.910 --> 00:25:02.820
outbreak, the long-term
sequela that those people are

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:04.830
experiencing.

00:25:04.830 --> 00:25:07.810
Then we are going to
have Dr. Celina Turchi

00:25:07.810 --> 00:25:10.480
Martelli from Brazil,
who played a really

00:25:10.480 --> 00:25:13.960
important role in the
Brazilian response to Zika.

00:25:13.960 --> 00:25:17.100
And in the middle
of all the chaos,

00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:21.160
she is going to tell us how you
can actually design and conduct

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:25.390
epidemiological studies, how
you can foster collaborations

00:25:25.390 --> 00:25:27.670
between many different
bodies of research--

00:25:27.670 --> 00:25:30.220
and everybody wants to come
first and be the first one

00:25:30.220 --> 00:25:31.750
to say something new--

00:25:31.750 --> 00:25:34.630
and how you actually
promote sharing of data.

00:25:34.630 --> 00:25:38.230
All those three issues are hard
to do in normal conditions.

00:25:38.230 --> 00:25:40.960
Under an epidemic, they
are way much harder.

00:25:40.960 --> 00:25:44.650
So Celina is going to tell us
how she managed to do this.

00:25:44.650 --> 00:25:47.980
So together, those
three different talks,

00:25:47.980 --> 00:25:51.400
we're going to walk us through
three different aspects.

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:55.120
So the first one is how we
can mobilize researchers

00:25:55.120 --> 00:25:57.790
to do the right thing
at the right time

00:25:57.790 --> 00:26:01.690
and generate much-needed
evidence to be able to respond

00:26:01.690 --> 00:26:03.550
with the right policies.

00:26:03.550 --> 00:26:08.140
Second, we're going to
see how we can better

00:26:08.140 --> 00:26:11.080
track new and
re-emerging pathogens,

00:26:11.080 --> 00:26:15.370
leveraging on the very best
technology we have available.

00:26:15.370 --> 00:26:17.620
And last but not
least, we're going

00:26:17.620 --> 00:26:21.220
to see how we can assess
the long-term consequences

00:26:21.220 --> 00:26:25.090
of epidemic, largely neglected,
but extremely important.

00:26:25.090 --> 00:26:27.820
So without further
ado, let's get started.

