- Thank you, Marcia.

00:26:36.976 --> 00:26:38.600
And also, I want to
use the opportunity

00:26:38.600 --> 00:26:43.420
to thank the Radcliffe College
Institute for this invitation.

00:26:43.420 --> 00:26:46.420
So basically, I will
be talking about how

00:26:46.420 --> 00:26:50.380
we use genomics to characterize
and set up a surveillance

00:26:50.380 --> 00:26:54.850
system in West Africa and
how this has helped us

00:26:54.850 --> 00:26:56.920
and especially in
Nigeria dramatically

00:26:56.920 --> 00:27:01.480
to contain the last
Ebola outbreak in 2014.

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:04.236
So, and we do this
within a framework.

00:27:04.236 --> 00:27:06.610
And that is the African Center
of Excellence for Genomics

00:27:06.610 --> 00:27:07.630
of Infectious Diseases.

00:27:07.630 --> 00:27:11.290
And the center is a consortium
of academic and clinical

00:27:11.290 --> 00:27:12.730
studies in Africa.

00:27:12.730 --> 00:27:15.430
But in addition to that, we
have partners here, especially

00:27:15.430 --> 00:27:18.150
at Harvard at Broad Institute,
Tulane University, and then

00:27:18.150 --> 00:27:19.690
also partnering in the industry.

00:27:19.690 --> 00:27:21.640
And we work together
with these partners

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:24.700
in order to not only
develop genomic technology,

00:27:24.700 --> 00:27:28.150
but also translate those high
court technologies into tools

00:27:28.150 --> 00:27:31.810
that enable us to develop
rapid diagnostic tests to track

00:27:31.810 --> 00:27:35.640
these outbreaks, to track
diseases in the field.

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:37.820
So this partnership
is actually built

00:27:37.820 --> 00:27:40.100
on a very solid foundation
on the strong long-term

00:27:40.100 --> 00:27:41.605
collaboration between partners.

00:27:41.605 --> 00:27:44.230
And this partnership, because
of its success as a [INAUDIBLE],,

00:27:44.230 --> 00:27:47.030
it has attracted
new collaborations

00:27:47.030 --> 00:27:49.530
within the region.

00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:51.510
So, and why do we
focus on genomics?

00:27:51.510 --> 00:27:54.360
Basically because
of one single thing.

00:27:54.360 --> 00:27:58.780
It's the fact that the genome--
the whole genome project,

00:27:58.780 --> 00:28:03.780
and then the sequencing
of various organisms

00:28:03.780 --> 00:28:06.990
has brought tremendous progress
in the field of health,

00:28:06.990 --> 00:28:07.980
for instance.

00:28:07.980 --> 00:28:11.095
And Africa, you know,
really is not participating.

00:28:11.095 --> 00:28:12.720
And the lack of
participation of Africa

00:28:12.720 --> 00:28:14.910
is basically due to the
fact that there's no scale.

00:28:14.910 --> 00:28:16.220
There's no know-how.

00:28:16.220 --> 00:28:18.935
And there's a huge divide
between the West and Africa.

00:28:18.935 --> 00:28:20.310
And that's the
reason why we just

00:28:20.310 --> 00:28:22.143
decided to use the
genomic approach in order

00:28:22.143 --> 00:28:24.140
to narrow down the
gap, and also provide

00:28:24.140 --> 00:28:28.260
a needed knowledge in order
for African scientists

00:28:28.260 --> 00:28:32.020
to participate in the
genomic revolution.

00:28:32.020 --> 00:28:34.070
So our mission
actually is twofold.

00:28:34.070 --> 00:28:37.270
One is educational,
as I mentioned.

00:28:37.270 --> 00:28:43.300
And that is actually to
create a vibrant environment

00:28:43.300 --> 00:28:46.350
that is free of
external influence

00:28:46.350 --> 00:28:49.090
and that transcends
national boundaries

00:28:49.090 --> 00:28:53.200
in order to ensure relevant,
responsive, ethical, and

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:57.510
high-quality genomic
research in Africa.

00:28:57.510 --> 00:28:59.080
And the specific
aims of the program

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:00.730
is actually to develop--

00:29:00.730 --> 00:29:03.370
you know, train a critical
mass of well-trained African

00:29:03.370 --> 00:29:05.230
scientists to use
genomic knowledge

00:29:05.230 --> 00:29:09.910
to address important issues such
as elimination or eradication

00:29:09.910 --> 00:29:13.840
of infectious disease, and also
to create genomic curricula

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:17.920
on the continent to address the
issue of infectious diseases,

00:29:17.920 --> 00:29:22.090
and also to engage communities
in prevention and public health

00:29:22.090 --> 00:29:23.770
education.

00:29:23.770 --> 00:29:25.520
And this particular
aspect of this program

00:29:25.520 --> 00:29:27.978
that I'm going to be presenting
[INAUDIBLE] the achievement

00:29:27.978 --> 00:29:29.980
is actually supported
by the World Bank.

00:29:29.980 --> 00:29:33.040
But the research
component of this program

00:29:33.040 --> 00:29:34.930
is supported by NIH.

00:29:34.930 --> 00:29:37.600
And the goal is actually
to use field-deployable,

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:41.940
state-of-the-art technology
to identify pathogens driving

00:29:41.940 --> 00:29:43.447
febrile illnesses.

00:29:43.447 --> 00:29:45.280
The reason why we talk
about febrile illness

00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:47.920
is that fever is
actually the denominator

00:29:47.920 --> 00:29:52.090
for pretty much all infectious
diseases in the continent.

00:29:52.090 --> 00:29:54.730
In Africa, most of the time,
when you go down to hospital

00:29:54.730 --> 00:29:57.390
with a fever, the first
culprit is malaria.

00:29:57.390 --> 00:29:59.390
And after malaria, if
you're not getting better,

00:29:59.390 --> 00:30:00.909
they say it's typhoid.

00:30:00.909 --> 00:30:02.450
And when you go
through that process,

00:30:02.450 --> 00:30:04.991
if you have any other infection,
then the disease progresses,

00:30:04.991 --> 00:30:07.310
and eventually, you end
up in a very bad situation

00:30:07.310 --> 00:30:08.607
or you end up dead.

00:30:08.607 --> 00:30:10.190
And we've just
realized over the years

00:30:10.190 --> 00:30:13.790
that malaria is what
I call over-diagnosed

00:30:13.790 --> 00:30:16.340
and also anti-malaria
drugs are over-prescribed.

00:30:16.340 --> 00:30:18.200
And that actually
drive the whole process

00:30:18.200 --> 00:30:21.145
of drug resistance
on the continent.

00:30:21.145 --> 00:30:23.270
And we've heard that there
are many other pathogens

00:30:23.270 --> 00:30:27.140
circulating around that are
truly responsible for fevers

00:30:27.140 --> 00:30:30.560
that we see in 60% or 70%
of African patients that

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:32.720
find themselves in hospitals.

00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:34.610
So and as such, this
goal is actually

00:30:34.610 --> 00:30:36.190
to create a foundation
for Africans

00:30:36.190 --> 00:30:40.130
to actually carry out
very [INAUDIBLE] research

00:30:40.130 --> 00:30:41.457
on the African continent.

00:30:41.457 --> 00:30:43.040
The reason for
creating the foundation

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:45.081
is basically because we've
noticed over the years

00:30:45.081 --> 00:30:46.600
that not--

00:30:46.600 --> 00:30:48.620
I mean, Africans are
really not participating

00:30:48.620 --> 00:30:52.410
on the research involving
diseases on the continent.

00:30:52.410 --> 00:30:54.770
Samples are often
shipped out of Africa.

00:30:54.770 --> 00:30:55.812
And then they lose track.

00:30:55.812 --> 00:30:58.145
They have no idea of what's
going on with a sample band.

00:30:58.145 --> 00:31:00.770
And then the next thing they see
is actually publications out.

00:31:00.770 --> 00:31:04.030
So, and it is high time
that we can actually

00:31:04.030 --> 00:31:08.090
set up on the continent facility
to enable diagnosis and enable

00:31:08.090 --> 00:31:10.490
research so that
Africans can start

00:31:10.490 --> 00:31:12.620
addressing their problems.

00:31:12.620 --> 00:31:15.260
These two programs that I
just mentioned, if you see,

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:19.090
actually cross in
one particular area,

00:31:19.090 --> 00:31:21.560
and that is the area
of capacity building

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:22.792
in the field of genomics.

00:31:22.792 --> 00:31:24.375
And what we do with
these two programs

00:31:24.375 --> 00:31:27.890
is basically to just ensure that
we have genomic teaching labs

00:31:27.890 --> 00:31:30.290
that we've set up
on the continent.

00:31:30.290 --> 00:31:32.060
Develop that core
diagnostic facility

00:31:32.060 --> 00:31:34.730
to track infectious
diseases, and then

00:31:34.730 --> 00:31:37.190
also encourage
sustainable careers

00:31:37.190 --> 00:31:38.930
among African scientists.

00:31:38.930 --> 00:31:41.120
Through this program,
with our [INAUDIBLE],,

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:43.130
we've made some major progress.

00:31:43.130 --> 00:31:45.620
We've been able to add value
to what happens in Africa

00:31:45.620 --> 00:31:47.410
by reversing the brain drain.

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:49.640
I also make what
I call brain gain.

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:52.730
We've been able to track some
from young Africans in diaspora

00:31:52.730 --> 00:31:55.010
returning back and then
working together to address

00:31:55.010 --> 00:31:57.476
these major challenges.

00:31:57.476 --> 00:32:00.060
So overall, the overall goal
is actually to develop--

00:32:00.060 --> 00:32:02.440
I mean, to build the next
generation of African pathogen

00:32:02.440 --> 00:32:03.272
hunters.

00:32:03.272 --> 00:32:04.730
The reason being
that because we've

00:32:04.730 --> 00:32:06.340
been playing defense in Africa.

00:32:06.340 --> 00:32:08.810
And I think it's high time
to start playing offense.

00:32:08.810 --> 00:32:11.450
We've always been at
the receiving end.

00:32:11.450 --> 00:32:12.650
We've heard about it.

00:32:12.650 --> 00:32:18.110
Zika, malaria, typhoid, Lassa
fever, Ebola virus disease--

00:32:18.110 --> 00:32:19.130
name it.

00:32:19.130 --> 00:32:20.990
We're always at
the receiving end.

00:32:20.990 --> 00:32:22.640
I believe that now
it is high time

00:32:22.640 --> 00:32:24.556
to use the knowledge and
the technologies that

00:32:24.556 --> 00:32:27.980
are available to go down in
the dead bushes of Africa

00:32:27.980 --> 00:32:31.370
and hunt these pathogens,
characterize them,

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:32.870
and of lab diagnosis
against them

00:32:32.870 --> 00:32:34.760
before they come hunting us.

00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:36.070
I think it is high time.

00:32:36.070 --> 00:32:37.820
And that is one of--
that is a major goal,

00:32:37.820 --> 00:32:40.740
and the ultimate
goal, of our program.

00:32:40.740 --> 00:32:42.880
So, what are our achievements?

00:32:42.880 --> 00:32:48.030
I will take you back as just
the 2014 Ebola outbreak.

00:32:48.030 --> 00:32:51.740
As far back as March
2014 when Ebola

00:32:51.740 --> 00:32:55.470
was brewing in the [INAUDIBLE]
confinement of Guinea.

00:32:55.470 --> 00:32:57.340
And the world was looking away.

00:32:57.340 --> 00:33:01.790
The major health organization
were not bothered about this.

00:33:01.790 --> 00:33:03.050
We're very ambitious.

00:33:03.050 --> 00:33:05.330
I invited a group
of friends of mine

00:33:05.330 --> 00:33:06.950
from Harvard from
the Broad Institute,

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:08.960
from Tulane, and some
other institution.

00:33:08.960 --> 00:33:10.340
You can see the picture here.

00:33:10.340 --> 00:33:11.835
We sat in my lab.

00:33:11.835 --> 00:33:17.300
And we thought that we could
solve the Ebola problem

00:33:17.300 --> 00:33:20.220
if it ever spread.

00:33:20.220 --> 00:33:21.402
We were very ambitious.

00:33:21.402 --> 00:33:22.860
We thought that
with a little skill

00:33:22.860 --> 00:33:24.630
and knowledge that
we have, we could

00:33:24.630 --> 00:33:26.470
address that major problem.

00:33:26.470 --> 00:33:28.740
But there was something that
came out of that meeting.

00:33:28.740 --> 00:33:32.040
And that thing was we had
a premonition that Ebola

00:33:32.040 --> 00:33:33.240
was going to spill over.

00:33:33.240 --> 00:33:36.625
And if Ebola spilled
over, what could we do?

00:33:36.625 --> 00:33:39.716
We identified diagnosis
as one of the major gaps.

00:33:39.716 --> 00:33:41.340
And what we did was
actually to go back

00:33:41.340 --> 00:33:43.440
on the side of
developing diagnostics--

00:33:43.440 --> 00:33:46.200
better diagnosis
for Ebola, and then

00:33:46.200 --> 00:33:49.290
train people in Nigeria,
Sierra Leone, and Senegal

00:33:49.290 --> 00:33:50.670
to diagnose Ebola.

00:33:50.670 --> 00:33:54.269
And as we rightly predicted, by
May 20, one of the technicians

00:33:54.269 --> 00:33:56.310
that we trained diagnosed
the first case of Ebola

00:33:56.310 --> 00:33:57.920
in Sierra Leone.

00:33:57.920 --> 00:34:02.780
And subsequently,
on July 22, I led

00:34:02.780 --> 00:34:05.620
a team in [INAUDIBLE] that
knew the first case of Ebola

00:34:05.620 --> 00:34:07.240
in Nigeria.

00:34:07.240 --> 00:34:09.199
The fact that we were
prepared and the fact

00:34:09.199 --> 00:34:13.420
that we were ready, for the case
of Nigeria, that single act,

00:34:13.420 --> 00:34:15.610
or that single fact
that we had this,

00:34:15.610 --> 00:34:19.414
was very critical to avert
one of the major health

00:34:19.414 --> 00:34:20.830
disasters that
could have happened

00:34:20.830 --> 00:34:22.449
in the history of mankind.

00:34:22.449 --> 00:34:25.090
That is preventing
the spread of Ebola

00:34:25.090 --> 00:34:28.989
in the city of 20 million,
22 million individuals

00:34:28.989 --> 00:34:31.190
in Lagos, Nigeria.

00:34:31.190 --> 00:34:32.870
We provided a
result within hours.

00:34:32.870 --> 00:34:37.070
And then we activated what I
call an emergency operation

00:34:37.070 --> 00:34:37.969
center.

00:34:37.969 --> 00:34:39.730
I worked with the
government for isolation

00:34:39.730 --> 00:34:42.620
and the containment
of individuals.

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:44.823
And that alone
was very critical.

00:34:44.823 --> 00:34:46.489
The other thing that
we did was actually

00:34:46.489 --> 00:34:49.489
what I call
[INAUDIBLE] because we

00:34:49.489 --> 00:34:52.560
had the technology, because
we believed in ourselves.

00:34:52.560 --> 00:34:55.590
So when the agencies that
were parachuted in Nigeria--

00:34:55.590 --> 00:34:57.570
you know [INAUDIBLE]
had control--

00:34:57.570 --> 00:35:00.074
arrived, we told them that
we knew what we were doing.

00:35:00.074 --> 00:35:01.990
And then we were able
to contain the outbreak.

00:35:01.990 --> 00:35:05.822
[APPLAUSE]

00:35:07.737 --> 00:35:09.570
Interestingly, we went
on in the first three

00:35:09.570 --> 00:35:10.609
weeks of the outbreak.

00:35:10.609 --> 00:35:12.150
But we were able to
do this basically

00:35:12.150 --> 00:35:14.691
because we've been able to-- we
achieved this feat in Nigeria

00:35:14.691 --> 00:35:17.670
because we were working on
a pathogen, a Category A

00:35:17.670 --> 00:35:19.530
agent like Lassa fever.

00:35:19.530 --> 00:35:22.740
And this agent is also supposed
to be as deadly as Ebola.

00:35:22.740 --> 00:35:26.430
But we were actually doing
this in [INAUDIBLE] facilities

00:35:26.430 --> 00:35:28.050
because we devised
ways of working

00:35:28.050 --> 00:35:31.200
with these pathogens in very
poor and limited-resource

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:32.271
cities.

00:35:32.271 --> 00:35:34.770
And this is what you'll see
what we're doing in Sierra Leone

00:35:34.770 --> 00:35:35.821
and in Nigeria.

00:35:35.821 --> 00:35:37.320
What we did in
Sierra Leone that was

00:35:37.320 --> 00:35:39.510
unique was the fact that because
we've been working on Lassa

00:35:39.510 --> 00:35:41.218
fever, when we identified
our first case,

00:35:41.218 --> 00:35:45.030
we also activated what we call
a contact-tracing mechanism

00:35:45.030 --> 00:35:47.460
that we used Lassa fever.

00:35:47.460 --> 00:35:49.860
And they were able to trace
the first case of Ebola

00:35:49.860 --> 00:35:52.830
in Sierra Leone to a
traditional healer who

00:35:52.830 --> 00:35:55.950
thought that he had all the
power to do to cure Lassa,

00:35:55.950 --> 00:35:58.080
not to cure Ebola, and
through that process,

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:01.582
was spreading that
across the region.

00:36:01.582 --> 00:36:03.540
But what we did in the
process was for the fact

00:36:03.540 --> 00:36:06.240
that we were actually
using-- doing some research

00:36:06.240 --> 00:36:08.750
and then understand use
metagenomics, for instance,

00:36:08.750 --> 00:36:11.580
as a way to understand what
was responsible for fevers

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:12.414
during the outbreak.

00:36:12.414 --> 00:36:13.663
As you can see, one of those--

00:36:13.663 --> 00:36:15.840
I mean, as you can see
that in the diagram below,

00:36:15.840 --> 00:36:17.430
you see many of
the cases that used

00:36:17.430 --> 00:36:18.971
to come to the Ebola
treatment center

00:36:18.971 --> 00:36:20.310
were not necessarily Ebola.

00:36:20.310 --> 00:36:23.380
But they were things like
malaria, HIV, and everything.

00:36:23.380 --> 00:36:25.380
So what happened in the
outbreak is that there's

00:36:25.380 --> 00:36:26.280
a lot of sense of panic.

00:36:26.280 --> 00:36:27.990
And everybody that
comes down with fever

00:36:27.990 --> 00:36:30.870
actually is sent to the
Ebola treatment center.

00:36:30.870 --> 00:36:33.509
What happened-- I mean, and then
the danger and the consequence

00:36:33.509 --> 00:36:35.550
of that is that you leave
your home very healthy,

00:36:35.550 --> 00:36:36.450
but then you come back.

00:36:36.450 --> 00:36:38.160
You're actually
infected with the virus,

00:36:38.160 --> 00:36:40.706
and then spread an outbreak.

00:36:40.706 --> 00:36:42.330
So what we also did
during the outbreak

00:36:42.330 --> 00:36:43.950
was actually to
convert a process that

00:36:43.950 --> 00:36:46.885
used to take a very long time
in a laboratory that would take

00:36:46.885 --> 00:36:48.010
a few months in laboratory.

00:36:48.010 --> 00:36:48.990
We did that in 10 days.

00:36:48.990 --> 00:36:51.630
That is basically from
collecting the sample

00:36:51.630 --> 00:36:55.070
to generate sequence data.

00:36:55.070 --> 00:36:58.570
And we were be able to
achieve this in 10 days.

00:36:58.570 --> 00:37:00.960
So we generated about
99 sequence data.

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:03.610
Within 10 days, and within the
first few days of the outbreak,

00:37:03.610 --> 00:37:06.500
I made these sequences available
to international community.

00:37:06.500 --> 00:37:08.430
We're not concerned
about generating data

00:37:08.430 --> 00:37:09.180
for publication.

00:37:09.180 --> 00:37:11.540
We're not concerned about fame.

00:37:11.540 --> 00:37:14.124
We're more concerned
about making information

00:37:14.124 --> 00:37:15.790
available to the
international community

00:37:15.790 --> 00:37:17.560
so that they can
use the sequence

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:20.310
data to generate drugs,
develop vaccines, or develop

00:37:20.310 --> 00:37:21.480
diagnostics.

00:37:21.480 --> 00:37:26.710
And the publication
came back months after.

00:37:26.710 --> 00:37:28.990
We're also in the process--

00:37:28.990 --> 00:37:32.350
you know, went on and then
work on developing methods

00:37:32.350 --> 00:37:34.516
to sequence Ebola
and then Lassa fever.

00:37:34.516 --> 00:37:35.890
I mean, this was
in collaboration

00:37:35.890 --> 00:37:38.620
with colleagues at Harvard
and at the Broad Institute.

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:41.410
And this method will actually
publish more or less like SOPs

00:37:41.410 --> 00:37:43.630
where anybody could
actually use it actively

00:37:43.630 --> 00:37:45.040
to repeat or
replicate what would

00:37:45.040 --> 00:37:46.660
we were doing in the laboratory.

00:37:46.660 --> 00:37:48.880
And that was also
very important.

00:37:48.880 --> 00:37:51.672
We use genomics
actually to understand

00:37:51.672 --> 00:37:55.570
the spread and the transmission
of Ebola in Sierra Leone

00:37:55.570 --> 00:37:56.410
during the outbreak.

00:37:56.410 --> 00:37:59.294
And as you can
see in this chart,

00:37:59.294 --> 00:38:01.710
you could see that you have
two different strains of Ebola

00:38:01.710 --> 00:38:08.210
entering Sierra Leone in-between
March and June 20, 2014.

00:38:08.210 --> 00:38:11.320
And I could see it through
the process by June 2013,

00:38:11.320 --> 00:38:14.620
the third strain that actually
entered, SL3, has taken over.

00:38:14.620 --> 00:38:16.830
So this was a strain
that was better adapted

00:38:16.830 --> 00:38:19.750
and had a better
transmission efficiency.

00:38:19.750 --> 00:38:23.080
We identified multiple
snips the strains.

00:38:23.080 --> 00:38:24.610
And they [INAUDIBLE]
confirmed from

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:27.640
human-to-human transmission,
and also confirmed the fact

00:38:27.640 --> 00:38:33.910
that there was no sources
outside the human-to-human

00:38:33.910 --> 00:38:35.799
transmission.

00:38:35.799 --> 00:38:37.590
Over time, we were able
to use genomic data

00:38:37.590 --> 00:38:41.380
to actually reconstitute
transmission in the region.

00:38:41.380 --> 00:38:43.650
And I don't know this
map will show it,

00:38:43.650 --> 00:38:45.370
but this was just
a video actually

00:38:45.370 --> 00:38:46.630
to show how this happened.

00:38:46.630 --> 00:38:48.760
The outbreak in Nigeria
was a little bit smaller--

00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:49.432
four months.

00:38:49.432 --> 00:38:50.890
But within the four
months, we were

00:38:50.890 --> 00:38:52.460
able to actually
use genomic data

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:53.830
and then use contact tracing.

00:38:53.830 --> 00:38:56.680
As you can see in those
two panels, A and B,

00:38:56.680 --> 00:38:59.350
you can actually
superimpose very well

00:38:59.350 --> 00:39:01.960
the genetic data and then
the contact-tracing data.

00:39:01.960 --> 00:39:05.500
And that actually
shows the power

00:39:05.500 --> 00:39:07.600
of genomics,
actually, in the field

00:39:07.600 --> 00:39:10.330
in order to understand
epidemiology and transmission

00:39:10.330 --> 00:39:12.220
of disease.

00:39:12.220 --> 00:39:14.680
So what we've been
doing over the years

00:39:14.680 --> 00:39:16.920
is actually to identify a
pathogen based on sequences

00:39:16.920 --> 00:39:18.461
and then use these
sequences as a way

00:39:18.461 --> 00:39:22.270
to develop new
tools for diagnosis.

00:39:22.270 --> 00:39:24.157
And that also was
being very helpful.

00:39:24.157 --> 00:39:26.240
During the four months of
the outbreak in Nigeria,

00:39:26.240 --> 00:39:29.050
we worked with partners, having
these sequences, in Africa,

00:39:29.050 --> 00:39:31.540
having the Ebola
sequences to generate

00:39:31.540 --> 00:39:34.710
a rapid diagnostic
test that could

00:39:34.710 --> 00:39:36.815
diagnose Ebola in 10 minutes.

00:39:36.815 --> 00:39:39.190
The reason why we actually
spent a lot of time developing

00:39:39.190 --> 00:39:41.860
that test is basically
because during an outbreak,

00:39:41.860 --> 00:39:44.500
we need to two main
things, speed and accuracy.

00:39:44.500 --> 00:39:47.080
We realized that it would
have taken about four hours

00:39:47.080 --> 00:39:48.520
to do one single diagnostics.

00:39:48.520 --> 00:39:50.140
And then we have
to think about--

00:39:50.140 --> 00:39:52.060
be creative about
ways of actually

00:39:52.060 --> 00:39:54.900
producing diagnostic
data almost in real time.

00:39:54.900 --> 00:39:57.687
And that-- when we actually did
that, we actually realized--

00:39:57.687 --> 00:39:59.770
I told them it was major
game changer in the field

00:39:59.770 --> 00:40:01.310
because clinicians
could actually

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:05.660
have this information
in near real time.

00:40:05.660 --> 00:40:06.471
We also used the--

00:40:06.471 --> 00:40:08.970
I mean, what we're also doing
is basically use genomic data,

00:40:08.970 --> 00:40:11.500
actually, to understand and
then discover pathogens.

00:40:11.500 --> 00:40:13.570
And in this case,
for instance, we're

00:40:13.570 --> 00:40:15.430
looking at patients
with febrile illness.

00:40:15.430 --> 00:40:17.889
And as you can see
in these two panels,

00:40:17.889 --> 00:40:19.930
you see healthy patients
and in febrile patients,

00:40:19.930 --> 00:40:24.220
you could see that you have
more in febrile patients

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:26.380
in terms of viruses, 8%--

00:40:26.380 --> 00:40:28.270
you know, 2% in people
that are healthy.

00:40:28.270 --> 00:40:30.210
So that shows that
viruses actually also

00:40:30.210 --> 00:40:33.370
could be very responsible for
many other febrile illness

00:40:33.370 --> 00:40:34.870
that I would see.

00:40:34.870 --> 00:40:37.630
And in the process, because
we also see some pathogen

00:40:37.630 --> 00:40:38.950
that have no heat.

00:40:38.950 --> 00:40:41.610
In this study, this is just
to illustrate how it's really

00:40:41.610 --> 00:40:43.780
what you use [INAUDIBLE]
to make a major discovery,

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:45.074
for instance, Nigeria.

00:40:45.074 --> 00:40:46.990
And in this case, control
study, for instance,

00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:49.690
we discovered two new
viruses in Nigeria.

00:40:49.690 --> 00:40:51.910
And these two new
viruses, we actually

00:40:51.910 --> 00:40:53.860
called them the
ipomovirus 1, it's

00:40:53.860 --> 00:40:56.140
a rhabdovirus that's
similar to rabies.

00:40:56.140 --> 00:40:58.750
And these viruses share
some very strong similarity

00:40:58.750 --> 00:41:00.640
to the [INAUDIBLE] virus
that was discovered

00:41:00.640 --> 00:41:02.860
in DRC Congo in 2012.

00:41:02.860 --> 00:41:04.480
And that is all--
that was shown to be

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:08.004
responsible for some kind
of viral hemorrhagic fevers.

00:41:08.004 --> 00:41:09.670
But then that shows,
actually, the power

00:41:09.670 --> 00:41:12.010
behind the public
discovery platform that we

00:41:12.010 --> 00:41:14.170
have because having
discovered these viruses,

00:41:14.170 --> 00:41:17.380
we also went on and then
developed new diagnostics

00:41:17.380 --> 00:41:18.234
for them.

00:41:18.234 --> 00:41:19.900
But what is interesting
about this story

00:41:19.900 --> 00:41:22.400
is basically that when we went
back to develop the diagnosis

00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:25.050
and went back to the community,
even though these viruses were

00:41:25.050 --> 00:41:29.020
new, 80% of people in those
communities were highly exposed

00:41:29.020 --> 00:41:31.720
and had a lot of antibodies
against this virus.

00:41:31.720 --> 00:41:33.970
So it shows clearly that
there are many pathogens that

00:41:33.970 --> 00:41:36.053
are circulating in our
community-- are circulating

00:41:36.053 --> 00:41:37.480
around that we don't know about.

00:41:37.480 --> 00:41:38.680
But then we need
to use technology

00:41:38.680 --> 00:41:41.290
to actually discover them and
see how we can actually develop

00:41:41.290 --> 00:41:43.580
diagnostics and [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:43.580 --> 00:41:46.590
So using, again,
genomic technology,

00:41:46.590 --> 00:41:48.100
we are able to understand--

00:41:48.100 --> 00:41:51.141
I mean, the origin and the
spread of a very old virus

00:41:51.141 --> 00:41:51.640
in Nigeria--

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:53.830
not very old, but a
Lassa fever virus that

00:41:53.830 --> 00:41:57.250
is very similar to
Ebola in many ways.

00:41:57.250 --> 00:41:59.670
And this diagram
actually shows you--

00:41:59.670 --> 00:42:02.590
and this is a study
by Kristian Andersen,

00:42:02.590 --> 00:42:03.910
a friend, a colleague of mine.

00:42:03.910 --> 00:42:06.720
So, and here, we could show
you that this virus that we'll

00:42:06.720 --> 00:42:08.380
call Lassa fever
has been circulating

00:42:08.380 --> 00:42:12.030
in present-day Nigeria
about 1,600 years ago,

00:42:12.030 --> 00:42:14.654
and circulating within
Nigeria for 600 years,

00:42:14.654 --> 00:42:16.570
and then moved out of
Nigeria about 400 years,

00:42:16.570 --> 00:42:17.867
moving westward.

00:42:17.867 --> 00:42:19.450
And then in the
field, we can actually

00:42:19.450 --> 00:42:22.750
see the differences
between an old virus that

00:42:22.750 --> 00:42:25.339
is very old in one country,
and then moved freshly

00:42:25.339 --> 00:42:26.130
into a new country.

00:42:26.130 --> 00:42:27.815
When you look at the
pathogenesis of--

00:42:27.815 --> 00:42:32.290
or philosophy between
Sierra Leone and Nigeria,

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:34.114
they are very different.

00:42:34.114 --> 00:42:36.030
We also used that to
develop new technologies.

00:42:36.030 --> 00:42:40.572
But then we use the epitome that
we sequenced in those viruses

00:42:40.572 --> 00:42:42.030
to develop a rapid
diagnostic test.

00:42:42.030 --> 00:42:44.180
We called it [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:44.180 --> 00:42:46.920
And that-- we use that now
as a way to help the Nigerian

00:42:46.920 --> 00:42:49.340
government to look at--

00:42:49.340 --> 00:42:51.602
to set up a surveillance system.

00:42:51.602 --> 00:42:54.060
What we've done over the years
is not just only do science,

00:42:54.060 --> 00:42:56.476
but also to train the next
generation of pathogen hunters.

00:42:56.476 --> 00:42:58.635
So we set up with a
genomic training program.

00:42:58.635 --> 00:43:00.510
And we do this in
collaboration with Harvard.

00:43:00.510 --> 00:43:03.630
And then we started in 2014 with
11 students from two countries.

00:43:03.630 --> 00:43:06.240
As you can see, the list
is growing over the years.

00:43:06.240 --> 00:43:08.420
And this year, we're
actually at 23 students

00:43:08.420 --> 00:43:10.740
from eight different countries.

00:43:10.740 --> 00:43:12.690
And here, you can
see, for instance,

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:15.630
the training programs, the
kind of topics the we cover.

00:43:15.630 --> 00:43:17.430
And pictures here could
show you very young

00:43:17.430 --> 00:43:18.680
Africans that we're training.

00:43:18.680 --> 00:43:21.360
But apart from just training
them, what we train them to do

00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:23.960
is-- we worked with
the Derek Bok Center

00:43:23.960 --> 00:43:26.450
here at Harvard to enable
them to use videos.

00:43:26.450 --> 00:43:28.260
And it is videos
I actually posted.

00:43:28.260 --> 00:43:30.120
And then they serve as
MOOCs so that people

00:43:30.120 --> 00:43:32.774
that are not privileged
to be in a place

00:43:32.774 --> 00:43:35.190
in like Harvard at least could
have access to those videos

00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:38.464
and then learn and
educate themselves.

00:43:38.464 --> 00:43:40.380
So, what we've done is
actually training them.

00:43:40.380 --> 00:43:42.629
But not just training them,
but we also accompany them

00:43:42.629 --> 00:43:43.470
with infrastructure.

00:43:43.470 --> 00:43:45.510
So we've set up
next-generation sequencing

00:43:45.510 --> 00:43:49.260
in Nigeria, in Senegal, and in
Sierra Leone early this year.

00:43:49.260 --> 00:43:51.240
So the trainings
actually have facilities

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:52.510
that they can go back and use.

00:43:52.510 --> 00:43:56.900
We also organize workshops
and genomics workshop series

00:43:56.900 --> 00:43:58.860
in Nigeria or in Africa.

00:43:58.860 --> 00:44:01.350
And we've trained over 600
students over the past three

00:44:01.350 --> 00:44:02.220
years.

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:04.860
And then we have 21
doctoral students and then

00:44:04.860 --> 00:44:07.950
46 master's degree students
within the program.

00:44:07.950 --> 00:44:10.350
The whole idea is actually to
translate genomic sciences,

00:44:10.350 --> 00:44:13.956
for instance, into tools that
will enable us in the future.

00:44:13.956 --> 00:44:15.580
As you could see
here, that it's coming

00:44:15.580 --> 00:44:17.460
from a high court,
high-tech technology,

00:44:17.460 --> 00:44:20.460
and then bring it
down to a level

00:44:20.460 --> 00:44:23.130
that we can actually
use in the field

00:44:23.130 --> 00:44:25.080
with small, portable
equipment that

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:26.400
enable diagnosis in the field.

00:44:29.360 --> 00:44:34.910
So, whatever we're doing
actually is not stopping.

00:44:34.910 --> 00:44:38.429
What we've also done is actually
to set up an outreach program.

00:44:38.429 --> 00:44:40.220
And this outreach
program that we've set up

00:44:40.220 --> 00:44:42.320
is actually to take it
outside the university

00:44:42.320 --> 00:44:43.790
and outside the ivory tower.

00:44:43.790 --> 00:44:45.380
As you can see here,
we have a program

00:44:45.380 --> 00:44:48.080
where we take it in high
school and inspire the kids

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:49.192
at a high-school level.

00:44:49.192 --> 00:44:51.650
But what we also do is actually
to educate science teachers

00:44:51.650 --> 00:44:53.960
in Africa because you can't
give what you don't have.

00:44:53.960 --> 00:44:55.772
So we spent time
training these kids,

00:44:55.772 --> 00:44:57.230
bringing them in
our labs, and then

00:44:57.230 --> 00:44:59.790
inspire them at that tender
age, and work with their teacher

00:44:59.790 --> 00:45:02.720
so they can go back with
biology, DNA, RNA, and protein

00:45:02.720 --> 00:45:04.935
models so that they
can use that to teach.

00:45:04.935 --> 00:45:07.310
And the students will also
have a summer training program

00:45:07.310 --> 00:45:08.810
that student comes
in, and then have

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:10.160
training in our laboratories.

00:45:10.160 --> 00:45:14.550
We've received support from
many institutions for the work

00:45:14.550 --> 00:45:15.390
that we're doing.

00:45:15.390 --> 00:45:17.300
But this-- what we've
done is actually--

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:18.759
I mean, it has a
lot of challenges.

00:45:18.759 --> 00:45:20.924
And one of those things,
one of the major challenges

00:45:20.924 --> 00:45:22.147
in the world is supply chain.

00:45:22.147 --> 00:45:23.480
Supply chain is a major problem.

00:45:23.480 --> 00:45:26.080
We're doing this kind of work in
Africa and we produce nothing.

00:45:26.080 --> 00:45:27.704
So how do we maintain
the supply chain?

00:45:27.704 --> 00:45:30.440
So what we do basically to
maintain our supply chain

00:45:30.440 --> 00:45:32.130
is actually to
convert our trainees

00:45:32.130 --> 00:45:34.296
that come to Harvard for
the summer training program

00:45:34.296 --> 00:45:36.120
into courier.

00:45:36.120 --> 00:45:37.930
So we load them with
[INAUDIBLE] and then

00:45:37.930 --> 00:45:39.680
with supplies and [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:42.784
And then when they get back,
then they can take them.

00:45:42.784 --> 00:45:44.200
But then we'll
also have problems.

00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:47.304
When you get back, then you
have an issue with customs.

00:45:47.304 --> 00:45:49.220
So, and customs will not
allow you to come in.

00:45:49.220 --> 00:45:51.675
So what we did in 2014
was actually to enable--

00:45:51.675 --> 00:45:53.050
we'd print them
a T-shirt, and it

00:45:53.050 --> 00:45:55.700
would say Ebola diagnostic
trainee is coming back.

00:45:55.700 --> 00:45:58.260
When they got to the border
and they were disturbing them,

00:45:58.260 --> 00:45:59.040
they all just saw Ebola.

00:45:59.040 --> 00:46:01.373
And then eventually, customs
asked them to [INAUDIBLE]..

