00:46:43.700 --> 00:46:46.040
I am here to tell you a
little bit about the work

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:48.770
that I've been doing in
the Democratic Republic

00:46:48.770 --> 00:46:50.979
of the Congo.

00:46:50.979 --> 00:46:52.520
The Democratic
Republic of the Congo,

00:46:52.520 --> 00:46:55.310
for those of you
who are not aware,

00:46:55.310 --> 00:46:58.400
is the largest country
in sub-Saharan Africa.

00:46:58.400 --> 00:47:00.410
I spent the last
15 years of my life

00:47:00.410 --> 00:47:04.340
working on emerging viruses
and doing what many people have

00:47:04.340 --> 00:47:06.290
told me over and over
again was impossible,

00:47:06.290 --> 00:47:09.170
which was to do really good
science in one of the most

00:47:09.170 --> 00:47:12.050
difficult places in the world.

00:47:12.050 --> 00:47:14.300
DRC, as you can see
from this slide here,

00:47:14.300 --> 00:47:17.060
just to give you some
context, is really big.

00:47:17.060 --> 00:47:19.760
It's a third of the size
of the United States.

00:47:19.760 --> 00:47:22.520
But unlike the United
States, there's

00:47:22.520 --> 00:47:25.580
only about a thousand miles
of road in the entire country,

00:47:25.580 --> 00:47:29.630
which can make it very, very
difficult to get much done.

00:47:29.630 --> 00:47:34.850
The DRC is also a place
where we've seen Ebola,

00:47:34.850 --> 00:47:41.030
not just in 2014, but all the
way back to 1976, 40 plus years

00:47:41.030 --> 00:47:45.440
ago, when the very
first outbreak

00:47:45.440 --> 00:47:52.100
of Ebola that occurred both on
the DRC side and in Sudan right

00:47:52.100 --> 00:47:57.080
across the border happened.

00:47:57.080 --> 00:48:03.050
Now, we all know today
that between December 2013

00:48:03.050 --> 00:48:07.730
and April 2016, the largest
epidemic of Ebola to date

00:48:07.730 --> 00:48:12.590
generated more than 28,000
cases that we know of and more

00:48:12.590 --> 00:48:18.000
than 11,000 deaths in the large
mobile populations of Guinea,

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:25.190
Liberia, and Sierra Leone, and
just barely in Nigeria as well.

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:29.090
This outbreak was very
important and provided

00:48:29.090 --> 00:48:34.310
a lot of opportunity to track
and understand survivors

00:48:34.310 --> 00:48:36.680
and generated a lot
of new insights.

00:48:36.680 --> 00:48:40.200
And that's very, very important.

00:48:40.200 --> 00:48:45.470
And it's very, very important
because the outbreak

00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:51.620
was able to end and did not
create more cases than we

00:48:51.620 --> 00:48:54.200
originally were worried about.

00:48:54.200 --> 00:48:59.060
Now, we were all thrilled when
the outbreak was declared over.

00:48:59.060 --> 00:49:01.880
And we-- but we've
heard this before--

00:49:01.880 --> 00:49:03.200
the outbreak is over.

00:49:03.200 --> 00:49:06.230
The outbreak was over in
Liberia, and all of a sudden,

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:09.630
there were several
cases that reemerged.

00:49:09.630 --> 00:49:13.490
And since that
outbreak has been over,

00:49:13.490 --> 00:49:15.080
there was actually
another outbreak

00:49:15.080 --> 00:49:18.590
in the Democratic Republic
of the Congo just in May.

00:49:18.590 --> 00:49:21.050
So just because the
outbreak ended--

00:49:21.050 --> 00:49:22.520
this very large
one-- doesn't mean

00:49:22.520 --> 00:49:25.490
that Ebola isn't still there.

00:49:25.490 --> 00:49:28.225
So, let's see here.

00:49:28.225 --> 00:49:29.096
How do I do this?

00:49:29.096 --> 00:49:30.440
OK, here we go.

00:49:30.440 --> 00:49:35.180
But what we do know now is
that for Ebola survivors,

00:49:35.180 --> 00:49:38.720
the outbreak isn't really over.

00:49:38.720 --> 00:49:41.240
We now know that
more than 50% or so

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:47.570
of the infected who pull through
still have long term effects.

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:49.950
Many of these people have
resumed their normal lives,

00:49:49.950 --> 00:49:51.680
but many of them are
still traumatized.

00:49:51.680 --> 00:49:54.380
They're struggling to process
the horrors they've seen,

00:49:54.380 --> 00:49:56.940
rejoin societies that
have shunned them.

00:49:56.940 --> 00:49:59.540
And the after-effects are
not just psychological.

00:49:59.540 --> 00:50:03.650
We know that there are many,
many after-effects of Ebola.

00:50:03.650 --> 00:50:07.970
We just don't know
exactly what they are.

00:50:07.970 --> 00:50:12.710
The studies that have been
ongoing in West Africa

00:50:12.710 --> 00:50:16.640
have showed us just a few
years after the outbreak

00:50:16.640 --> 00:50:19.650
that there are
ocular side effects.

00:50:19.650 --> 00:50:21.660
There are neurological
side effects,

00:50:21.660 --> 00:50:24.620
that people are actually
able to carry the virus

00:50:24.620 --> 00:50:27.680
and potentially shed the virus
from immune-protected sites

00:50:27.680 --> 00:50:31.230
for much longer than
anybody ever anticipated.

00:50:31.230 --> 00:50:34.190
And it's interesting that
nobody ever anticipated this

00:50:34.190 --> 00:50:39.530
because it turns out there are
a lot of survivors to study.

00:50:39.530 --> 00:50:44.360
What we know about right now
from these studies from 2014

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:49.470
going forward is there a lot
of things that can happen.

00:50:49.470 --> 00:50:53.250
But the question is, what else?

00:50:53.250 --> 00:50:56.220
I think that it's
important for me

00:50:56.220 --> 00:50:58.110
to invoke a little
bit of baseball

00:50:58.110 --> 00:51:00.290
since the Dodgers are
actually in the World Series.

00:51:00.290 --> 00:51:03.870
But it's really true that
what we've learned about Ebola

00:51:03.870 --> 00:51:06.870
is that it really-- it
isn't over until it's over.

00:51:06.870 --> 00:51:11.830
And the big question
is, when is it over?

00:51:11.830 --> 00:51:17.570
Well, and there are a lot
more questions about Ebola

00:51:17.570 --> 00:51:19.860
that we still have to answer.

00:51:19.860 --> 00:51:24.600
We don't know how long can
somebody transmit Ebola virus.

00:51:24.600 --> 00:51:27.210
How long does it
stay in these sites?

00:51:27.210 --> 00:51:29.190
For example, if
we can still find

00:51:29.190 --> 00:51:32.820
Ebola in the fluids
of the eye, are

00:51:32.820 --> 00:51:35.790
ophthalmologists at risk
for acquiring infection long

00:51:35.790 --> 00:51:38.940
after survival from infection?

00:51:38.940 --> 00:51:41.180
Are survivors protected
from long term--

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:43.050
from future outbreaks?

00:51:43.050 --> 00:51:46.380
How long does the immunity last?

00:51:46.380 --> 00:51:48.030
Is there anything
that can be done

00:51:48.030 --> 00:51:50.970
to reduce these after-effects?

00:51:50.970 --> 00:51:55.170
And what aside from the
clinical effects are there?

00:51:55.170 --> 00:51:57.610
We know that there
are economic effects.

00:51:57.610 --> 00:52:00.090
We know that there
are societal effects.

00:52:00.090 --> 00:52:02.490
None of these things do
we have any information

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:06.660
about further than four
years after this outbreak.

00:52:06.660 --> 00:52:12.400
Now, one would think there
have been outbreaks since 1976.

00:52:12.400 --> 00:52:15.540
So we ought to have
a lot of information.

00:52:15.540 --> 00:52:19.230
But actually, until this
recent Ebola outbreak,

00:52:19.230 --> 00:52:21.570
the longest study
looking at survivorship

00:52:21.570 --> 00:52:26.420
was only 2 and 1/2
years after an outbreak.

00:52:26.420 --> 00:52:29.690
And that was done in 1995.

00:52:29.690 --> 00:52:32.240
The 1995 outbreak--
there were studies

00:52:32.240 --> 00:52:34.740
that were done 2 and
1/2 years afterwards.

00:52:34.740 --> 00:52:37.970
And much like what we've
been hearing about,

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:40.190
the outbreak happens,
we think it's over,

00:52:40.190 --> 00:52:43.060
and we move onto the next thing.

00:52:43.060 --> 00:52:48.450
Well, we do have cohorts
in the Democratic Republic

00:52:48.450 --> 00:52:52.440
of the Congo that are there
and can provide very, very

00:52:52.440 --> 00:52:54.780
important information.

00:52:54.780 --> 00:52:57.690
In DRC, we've had
eight outbreaks--

00:52:57.690 --> 00:53:04.270
1976 all the way
through now, to 2017.

00:53:04.270 --> 00:53:06.310
So what my program
is doing is we're

00:53:06.310 --> 00:53:08.410
going back and looking
at these survivors

00:53:08.410 --> 00:53:12.850
from 1976, 1995, and 2014.

00:53:12.850 --> 00:53:15.040
So we have three really
unique groups that

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:17.200
are roughly 20 years apart.

00:53:17.200 --> 00:53:19.960
And what we hope is to better
understand the long-term health

00:53:19.960 --> 00:53:24.010
consequences of infection to
determine if survivors develop

00:53:24.010 --> 00:53:26.500
immunity that will protect
them from future infections,

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:29.200
assess whether previously
infected people can transmit

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:32.830
the virus still, to
understand all of these things

00:53:32.830 --> 00:53:34.270
that I just brought up.

00:53:34.270 --> 00:53:38.470
We really don't have
any information.

00:53:38.470 --> 00:53:41.300
So we think, great, no problem.

00:53:41.300 --> 00:53:41.970
You just go.

00:53:41.970 --> 00:53:42.945
You're going to find
these survivors.

00:53:42.945 --> 00:53:44.174
You get their phone number.

00:53:44.174 --> 00:53:45.090
You get their address.

00:53:45.090 --> 00:53:47.820
Maybe you send them an email.

00:53:47.820 --> 00:53:49.520
No problem.

00:53:49.520 --> 00:53:53.150
Well, it's not so easy in DRC.

00:53:53.150 --> 00:53:57.890
The '76 survivors and
the 1995 survivors

00:53:57.890 --> 00:54:00.780
happened before the
civil war in DRC.

00:54:00.780 --> 00:54:02.940
And so, all of the
records were lost.

00:54:02.940 --> 00:54:04.020
There were no records.

00:54:04.020 --> 00:54:07.680
So I went back to the
original investigators

00:54:07.680 --> 00:54:12.600
from the '76 and '95 outbreaks
and asked them for their notes.

00:54:12.600 --> 00:54:15.600
Well, for especially
from the '76 outbreak,

00:54:15.600 --> 00:54:17.430
there were no
electronic records.

00:54:17.430 --> 00:54:22.290
And so, I had some
very, very nice help

00:54:22.290 --> 00:54:25.110
from people like Peter
Piot and David Heymann who

00:54:25.110 --> 00:54:27.630
went into their garages
and their basements

00:54:27.630 --> 00:54:30.900
and their attics and found
their handwritten notes.

00:54:30.900 --> 00:54:33.390
And with this
information and the map

00:54:33.390 --> 00:54:37.170
that you can see
up here, which was

00:54:37.170 --> 00:54:40.590
about the same as the
map that still existed

00:54:40.590 --> 00:54:44.250
in Yambuku in this site,
I went about the business

00:54:44.250 --> 00:54:46.930
of finding survivors.

00:54:46.930 --> 00:54:49.510
And to my surprise and
to everybody else's,

00:54:49.510 --> 00:54:56.530
we found of 38 people that we
knew were infected in 1976,

00:54:56.530 --> 00:55:02.200
we found 14 of them still alive
in these very small villages.

00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:04.900
And so one by one, we
went through the forest,

00:55:04.900 --> 00:55:06.760
found these people,
and asked if we

00:55:06.760 --> 00:55:10.090
can study them and understand
their experience a little bit

00:55:10.090 --> 00:55:11.860
better.

00:55:11.860 --> 00:55:13.540
Well, but finding
them is one thing.

00:55:13.540 --> 00:55:16.300
But then you have to take
some samples from them.

00:55:16.300 --> 00:55:19.120
And we're not just talking
about taking some blood

00:55:19.120 --> 00:55:22.510
and putting it on a
dried blood spot card

00:55:22.510 --> 00:55:24.790
or taking a couple
tubes of blood

00:55:24.790 --> 00:55:27.140
and putting it in
my refrigerator.

00:55:27.140 --> 00:55:31.390
You know, it takes a
little bit more than that.

00:55:31.390 --> 00:55:34.120
And what I think our
study site has proven

00:55:34.120 --> 00:55:38.150
is that it is possible to do
really good science in very,

00:55:38.150 --> 00:55:39.550
very difficult situations.

00:55:39.550 --> 00:55:44.620
So this here is our
nice, little lab

00:55:44.620 --> 00:55:49.600
that we were offered by the
Ministry of Health in Yambuku.

00:55:49.600 --> 00:55:54.240
And so we brought all of these
supplies in this nice hut.

00:55:54.240 --> 00:55:56.800
We cleaned it up a
little bit and made

00:55:56.800 --> 00:56:03.630
sure that the goats and the
chickens were out of the room.

00:56:03.630 --> 00:56:06.400
And so that it was really
possible to do great science,

00:56:06.400 --> 00:56:08.530
to be able to isolate
B cells and T cells,

00:56:08.530 --> 00:56:10.990
which might be able to lead
to vaccines and therapeutics

00:56:10.990 --> 00:56:13.370
in these conditions.

00:56:13.370 --> 00:56:17.510
And we only have the
preliminary data at this point.

00:56:17.510 --> 00:56:18.770
There's a lot more to do.

00:56:18.770 --> 00:56:21.470
But thus far, one of the
very interesting things

00:56:21.470 --> 00:56:25.190
that we've found is that these
survivors from 40 years ago

00:56:25.190 --> 00:56:28.580
still have strong
antibody responses--

00:56:28.580 --> 00:56:30.890
every single one of them.

00:56:30.890 --> 00:56:33.470
And not only that,
50% of these people

00:56:33.470 --> 00:56:37.580
had the ability to
neutralize Ebola virus

00:56:37.580 --> 00:56:40.630
all of these years later.

00:56:40.630 --> 00:56:44.500
We've also found that there are
evidence of long-term effects.

00:56:44.500 --> 00:56:47.280
There's a lot more
work to be done.

00:56:47.280 --> 00:56:50.510
But we have just
started to find out

00:56:50.510 --> 00:56:53.060
all of this very
important information that

00:56:53.060 --> 00:56:58.550
has the opportunity to shed
light on what these 16,000

00:56:58.550 --> 00:57:01.970
plus survivors in West
Africa may be facing,

00:57:01.970 --> 00:57:05.850
and all the other survivors
from all the other outbreaks.

00:57:05.850 --> 00:57:11.830
So, once we started
that work, we also

00:57:11.830 --> 00:57:15.190
realized that there
was a lot of questions

00:57:15.190 --> 00:57:17.650
about asymptomatic
infection-- about people that

00:57:17.650 --> 00:57:20.890
might get infected but never
show any signs or symptoms

00:57:20.890 --> 00:57:23.170
and how many of them existed.

00:57:23.170 --> 00:57:26.260
And over the last couple of
years with the Ebola outbreak

00:57:26.260 --> 00:57:29.680
in West Africa, we've
now gotten good evidence

00:57:29.680 --> 00:57:36.370
that people who get Ebola
don't always show symptoms.

00:57:36.370 --> 00:57:40.020
So I thought, well, health
care workers are a really good

00:57:40.020 --> 00:57:42.270
population to look at.

00:57:42.270 --> 00:57:44.080
They're on the front lines.

00:57:44.080 --> 00:57:46.860
They're at greatest
risk for infection, in

00:57:46.860 --> 00:57:48.450
particular in the
kind of conditions

00:57:48.450 --> 00:57:50.400
that they're working
in, without the kind

00:57:50.400 --> 00:57:55.260
of personal protective equipment
that people in this room

00:57:55.260 --> 00:57:59.150
may be used to when
they go into a hospital.

00:57:59.150 --> 00:58:01.750
So we started taking samples
from health care workers in all

00:58:01.750 --> 00:58:03.280
of these sites
where there had been

00:58:03.280 --> 00:58:06.040
Ebola outbreaks and a few
sites where there hadn't been,

00:58:06.040 --> 00:58:08.920
just to compare.

00:58:08.920 --> 00:58:12.590
And we found some very,
very interesting results.

00:58:12.590 --> 00:58:16.200
We found that health
care workers had very,

00:58:16.200 --> 00:58:21.020
very high rates of Ebola,
surprisingly high rates

00:58:21.020 --> 00:58:24.470
of Ebola antibody evidence
that they had been previously

00:58:24.470 --> 00:58:31.340
exposed to Ebola, and much, much
more so than in the sites where

00:58:31.340 --> 00:58:35.030
there had never been
an outbreak reported,

00:58:35.030 --> 00:58:38.900
suggesting that not only
did these people have

00:58:38.900 --> 00:58:42.110
the opportunity to get
infected more often--

00:58:42.110 --> 00:58:44.300
which isn't really surprising--

00:58:44.300 --> 00:58:49.200
but that there is
something going on.

00:58:49.200 --> 00:58:52.290
Now, "health care worker"
is a very broad term,

00:58:52.290 --> 00:58:54.500
and can mean many, many things.

00:58:54.500 --> 00:58:57.470
To most of us here, you
think of a doctor or a nurse

00:58:57.470 --> 00:58:59.960
or a midwife or a lab tech.

00:58:59.960 --> 00:59:05.720
But in places like
Central and West Africa,

00:59:05.720 --> 00:59:09.320
those are not necessarily
the most common providers.

00:59:09.320 --> 00:59:11.930
We really, really
see a lot more people

00:59:11.930 --> 00:59:13.870
going to informal
health care workers--

00:59:13.870 --> 00:59:16.490
to what we would consider
traditional healers,

00:59:16.490 --> 00:59:23.750
to pastors, to local figures who
can go and help them in a way

00:59:23.750 --> 00:59:25.770
that people understand
much better.

00:59:25.770 --> 00:59:26.990
They're more accessible.

00:59:26.990 --> 00:59:29.480
They're less expensive.

00:59:29.480 --> 00:59:33.170
They may take for
payment instead of money

00:59:33.170 --> 00:59:34.760
you could work in their fields.

00:59:34.760 --> 00:59:39.950
You can give them food
that you grow yourself.

00:59:39.950 --> 00:59:42.230
So those are-- those
informal health

00:59:42.230 --> 00:59:44.340
care workers are actually
very, very important.

00:59:44.340 --> 00:59:46.250
And once again,
interestingly, we

00:59:46.250 --> 00:59:49.460
found that these informal,
traditional health

00:59:49.460 --> 00:59:54.020
care providers were also
people who were highly exposed.

00:59:57.490 --> 00:59:59.860
What's interesting is you
think, OK, well, fine.

00:59:59.860 --> 01:00:01.900
There have been Ebola
outbreaks in these sites.

01:00:01.900 --> 01:00:03.275
So it makes sense
that people who

01:00:03.275 --> 01:00:07.810
were in that area at the time
might have been infected.

01:00:07.810 --> 01:00:11.140
But interestingly, in
Yambuku, where the outbreak

01:00:11.140 --> 01:00:14.680
happened in 1976,
those people who

01:00:14.680 --> 01:00:19.397
were born after 1977, after the
outbreak was declared over--

01:00:19.397 --> 01:00:20.980
and I know now we
all know that "over"

01:00:20.980 --> 01:00:23.440
doesn't necessarily mean over--

01:00:23.440 --> 01:00:26.110
but "over."

01:00:26.110 --> 01:00:30.640
Those people that were
born after the outbreak--

01:00:30.640 --> 01:00:36.940
we found almost as high rates
of antibody in those people

01:00:36.940 --> 01:00:39.760
as the people who had been
alive during the outbreak, which

01:00:39.760 --> 01:00:43.330
suggests that Ebola
is still circulating

01:00:43.330 --> 01:00:50.880
in these populations long
after it disappears from view.

01:00:50.880 --> 01:00:55.500
So of course, now there are
more questions than answers.

01:00:55.500 --> 01:00:59.880
We wonder is Ebola virus
circulating silently in DRC?

01:00:59.880 --> 01:01:01.740
Well, our preliminary
results suggest

01:01:01.740 --> 01:01:03.940
that that may be the case.

01:01:03.940 --> 01:01:07.620
How are asymptomatically
infected people

01:01:07.620 --> 01:01:08.945
acquiring infection?

01:01:08.945 --> 01:01:10.320
Are there certain
groups that are

01:01:10.320 --> 01:01:13.120
more likely to be
infected than others?

01:01:13.120 --> 01:01:15.330
Can asymptomatically
infected individuals

01:01:15.330 --> 01:01:17.700
transmit the virus as well?

01:01:17.700 --> 01:01:21.980
What role do they play
in Ebola transmission?

01:01:21.980 --> 01:01:25.790
And do these people also
have long-term after-effects?

01:01:25.790 --> 01:01:28.220
We really have no idea.

01:01:28.220 --> 01:01:32.140
And although we have known about
Ebola for a very long time,

01:01:32.140 --> 01:01:36.350
we've not gotten to the
bottom of these questions.

01:01:36.350 --> 01:01:39.620
The thing is is we're
really running out of time.

01:01:39.620 --> 01:01:43.890
The aperture for doing
these studies is closing.

01:01:43.890 --> 01:01:46.730
The populations that we're
working with are aging.

01:01:46.730 --> 01:01:52.610
And the natural life expectancy
for a Congolese person is 57.

01:01:52.610 --> 01:01:55.550
The outbreak now
happened 42 years ago.

01:01:55.550 --> 01:01:57.540
And many of these
people were adults.

01:01:57.540 --> 01:01:59.300
In fact, when I started
doing this study,

01:01:59.300 --> 01:02:00.690
I said I found 14 survivors.

01:02:00.690 --> 01:02:02.240
Those were the 14
survivors that we

01:02:02.240 --> 01:02:04.247
were able to collect
samples from,

01:02:04.247 --> 01:02:06.080
where there were two
other survivors that we

01:02:06.080 --> 01:02:09.020
found and made contact
with, but were not

01:02:09.020 --> 01:02:11.570
able to get back to in time
before they passed away.

01:02:11.570 --> 01:02:15.740
One was 95 and one was 59.

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:17.570
So the aperture
really is closing

01:02:17.570 --> 01:02:20.630
to do these kinds
of studies, not just

01:02:20.630 --> 01:02:23.430
for the survivors
that we know about,

01:02:23.430 --> 01:02:26.600
but for those asymptomatically
infected survivors

01:02:26.600 --> 01:02:30.350
from these very,
very early outbreaks.

01:02:30.350 --> 01:02:32.980
And so, this is the
kind of work that we

01:02:32.980 --> 01:02:35.650
are trying to move forward
with as quickly as we possibly

01:02:35.650 --> 01:02:38.430
can to gather as
much information

01:02:38.430 --> 01:02:42.250
and to be able to capture
samples in history

01:02:42.250 --> 01:02:45.580
and epidemiologic data--

01:02:45.580 --> 01:02:48.160
everything that we
possibly can and archive it

01:02:48.160 --> 01:02:52.630
so that as technologies
improve, as we understand more

01:02:52.630 --> 01:02:55.736
about Ebola in general, not only
can we make use of the samples

01:02:55.736 --> 01:02:57.610
that we're collecting
now and the information

01:02:57.610 --> 01:02:59.443
we're collecting now,
but that we're banking

01:02:59.443 --> 01:03:01.000
it for the future
so we don't again

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:05.590
have this problem of forgetting
to look at what we should

01:03:05.590 --> 01:03:07.784
have looked at a long time ago.

01:03:07.784 --> 01:03:08.748
Thank you.

01:03:08.748 --> 01:03:12.604
[APPLAUSE]

01:03:18.390 --> 01:03:19.170
- Terrific, Anne.

01:03:19.170 --> 01:03:23.260
So now, we're going to move
to our last speaker, Celina

01:03:23.260 --> 01:03:25.950
Turchi, who is really
going to talk about how

01:03:25.950 --> 01:03:28.290
you respond to a
major epidemic when

01:03:28.290 --> 01:03:29.480
you are in the middle of it.

01:03:34.360 --> 01:03:36.250
- Good morning.

01:03:36.250 --> 01:03:39.150
What a challenge to
talk after those two.

01:03:39.150 --> 01:03:43.360
But I would like to first
thank the organizers

01:03:43.360 --> 01:03:47.475
for this opportunity, To name
a few, crews in Pernambuco,

01:03:47.475 --> 01:03:52.560
Brazil, and the Microcephaly
Epidemic Research Group.

01:03:52.560 --> 01:03:56.760
I'm here to present some
insights of the public house

01:03:56.760 --> 01:04:01.430
response in the
recent Zika outbreak.

01:04:01.430 --> 01:04:05.280
And I love the title of
this symposium, "Contagion--

01:04:05.280 --> 01:04:07.740
Exploring Modern Epidemics."

01:04:07.740 --> 01:04:11.580
Because I think that Zika
was a very good example.

01:04:11.580 --> 01:04:16.110
So first, I would like
to have a brief context.

01:04:16.110 --> 01:04:20.270
What are vector-borne diseases
in complex, urban areas?

01:04:20.270 --> 01:04:26.340
So, in 2015, dengue
was considered

01:04:26.340 --> 01:04:29.280
a major problem in Brazil.

01:04:29.280 --> 01:04:36.000
1.5 million cases, 900 deaths
for dengue in one year.

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:40.560
Since the '80s, we have been
having dengue epidemics.

01:04:40.560 --> 01:04:43.710
And Brazil was one of the
most affected countries

01:04:43.710 --> 01:04:48.150
in Latin America, with the
four circulating serotypes

01:04:48.150 --> 01:04:50.960
from DEN-1 to DEN-4.

01:04:50.960 --> 01:04:55.280
So what we could say that
urban environments, climate--

01:04:55.280 --> 01:04:59.400
and favors all-way
around transmission

01:04:59.400 --> 01:05:03.600
of dengue with marked
seasonal patterns

01:05:03.600 --> 01:05:08.190
and explosive epidemics in
different areas of the country.

01:05:08.190 --> 01:05:10.230
That was the
scenario for dengue,

01:05:10.230 --> 01:05:16.110
and was the public
health's concern in 2015.

01:05:16.110 --> 01:05:19.050
But there was an alert
about the introduction

01:05:19.050 --> 01:05:22.510
of another virus that were
coming from the Caribbean.

01:05:22.510 --> 01:05:26.430
That was the chikungunya
virus that's an alpha virus.

01:05:26.430 --> 01:05:33.060
But this alert was just that
this disease was important

01:05:33.060 --> 01:05:34.260
because it gave--

01:05:34.260 --> 01:05:39.570
it brings this ability and could
cause these large epidemics.

01:05:39.570 --> 01:05:41.280
That was really known.

01:05:41.280 --> 01:05:45.120
And then something comes
as a mystery disease that

01:05:45.120 --> 01:05:50.690
was called by the public and by
the media, a mysterious disease

01:05:50.690 --> 01:05:52.680
that was a benign disease.

01:05:52.680 --> 01:05:56.580
It was a fever like most
of infectious disease.

01:05:56.580 --> 01:06:02.090
People didn't feel ill, so
it was considered kind of,

01:06:02.090 --> 01:06:04.080
don't worry about this disease.

01:06:04.080 --> 01:06:07.020
Let's call it
dengue-like illness.

01:06:07.020 --> 01:06:10.260
That's how doctors were
taught by the public house

01:06:10.260 --> 01:06:13.230
at the moment because
we knew nothing

01:06:13.230 --> 01:06:19.020
about the neurologic
context of the effects.

01:06:19.020 --> 01:06:21.960
So, that what happens.

01:06:21.960 --> 01:06:27.030
I need to go to this
map just to show you.

01:06:27.030 --> 01:06:30.220
Actually what we had--

01:06:30.220 --> 01:06:33.270
the green circles
is chikungunya.

01:06:33.270 --> 01:06:36.210
And red circles is Zika.

01:06:36.210 --> 01:06:44.430
And imagine in 2015, there was
The Lancet journal just wrote,

01:06:44.430 --> 01:06:47.760
Zika virus with a
question mark, following

01:06:47.760 --> 01:06:49.890
dengue and chikungunya.

01:06:49.890 --> 01:06:52.260
There was still
this question mark.

01:06:52.260 --> 01:06:54.460
Was it going to occur?

01:06:54.460 --> 01:06:57.300
And if we look at
the map, the alert

01:06:57.300 --> 01:06:59.940
was for chikungunya,
not for dengue.

01:06:59.940 --> 01:07:04.080
The big circles in
Brazil and elsewhere

01:07:04.080 --> 01:07:06.540
was for chikungunya
in the Americas,

01:07:06.540 --> 01:07:09.060
not for the dengue epidemics.

01:07:09.060 --> 01:07:11.560
But here, it is very
important to say

01:07:11.560 --> 01:07:16.670
that we've been hearing the
last speakers about Africa.

01:07:16.670 --> 01:07:21.810
Zika was known to be
in Africa since 1947.

01:07:21.810 --> 01:07:25.440
But for 60 years, the
epidemiology world

01:07:25.440 --> 01:07:29.540
just knew very little about it.

01:07:29.540 --> 01:07:34.220
I may say that we had
14 cases in humans

01:07:34.220 --> 01:07:36.500
published for 60 years.

01:07:36.500 --> 01:07:39.800
That was really a
medical curiosity.

01:07:39.800 --> 01:07:42.950
I imagine that moves
think infectious disease

01:07:42.950 --> 01:07:46.010
and trained
epidemiologists never

01:07:46.010 --> 01:07:48.350
heard about Zika, like myself.

01:07:48.350 --> 01:07:51.160
I had never heard about Zika.

01:07:51.160 --> 01:07:53.630
And virologists, the book--

01:07:53.630 --> 01:07:56.090
virologists had
just one paragraph

01:07:56.090 --> 01:07:58.180
saying about the zoonoses.

01:07:58.180 --> 01:07:59.690
But the first epidemic--

01:07:59.690 --> 01:08:03.160
the history of the
epidemic is started

01:08:03.160 --> 01:08:10.380
in [INAUDIBLE] of Ireland
and French Polynesia Islands.

01:08:10.380 --> 01:08:13.640
But they were a small
population areas.

01:08:13.640 --> 01:08:14.870
There were cases.

01:08:14.870 --> 01:08:15.890
There were cases.

01:08:15.890 --> 01:08:18.620
There were a lot of
asymptomatic cases.

01:08:18.620 --> 01:08:21.470
And the French
Polynesia reported

01:08:21.470 --> 01:08:25.460
the first neurologic
effect of Guillain-Barre.

01:08:25.460 --> 01:08:29.060
So if we go to that
dark spot here,

01:08:29.060 --> 01:08:31.859
that's Recife, the
northeast of Brazil.

01:08:31.859 --> 01:08:35.330
That's where we were at the
beginning of the epidemic.

01:08:35.330 --> 01:08:38.430
It was August.

01:08:38.430 --> 01:08:41.240
So, what was going on?

01:08:44.359 --> 01:08:47.660
The capital of
Recife in Pernambuco,

01:08:47.660 --> 01:08:51.109
northeast of Brazil,
was the epicenter

01:08:51.109 --> 01:08:53.990
of this microcephalic epidemic.

01:08:53.990 --> 01:08:55.819
We were at the front line.

01:08:55.819 --> 01:08:58.520
And what-- there
was a microcephaly

01:08:58.520 --> 01:09:00.649
with unknown etiology.

01:09:00.649 --> 01:09:03.684
We didn't know what to
look for because all

01:09:03.684 --> 01:09:09.080
the infectious disease and all
of the genetic disease supposed

01:09:09.080 --> 01:09:12.260
to cause microcephaly
were negative

01:09:12.260 --> 01:09:15.149
and didn't test positive
among these babies.

01:09:15.149 --> 01:09:18.800
So for that time, it
was an unknown cause.

01:09:18.800 --> 01:09:21.880
And remember when
those babies are born,

01:09:21.880 --> 01:09:25.939
and when the mothers were
affected several months before.

01:09:25.939 --> 01:09:29.600
So we couldn't get genetic
proofs at the moment

01:09:29.600 --> 01:09:33.140
to find it, nor we
did have lab tests

01:09:33.140 --> 01:09:35.330
so we could test immediately.

01:09:35.330 --> 01:09:37.370
Lab-- they weren't lab tests.

01:09:37.370 --> 01:09:42.350
There were lab tests in the CDC
that would take weeks to get.

01:09:42.350 --> 01:09:47.990
And even if we get
them, IGM and RTPCR

01:09:47.990 --> 01:09:51.930
aren't always positive
after such a long time.

01:09:51.930 --> 01:09:55.310
So looking back
in retrospective,

01:09:55.310 --> 01:10:00.950
we may say that Zika virus found
a large pool of susceptible

01:10:00.950 --> 01:10:06.460
individuals, abundant
presence of Aedes,

01:10:06.460 --> 01:10:11.440
good environmental conditions
in a densely urban population.

01:10:11.440 --> 01:10:14.980
This is good enough,
OK, to make it

01:10:14.980 --> 01:10:19.630
possible a range of possible
neurological outcomes,

01:10:19.630 --> 01:10:22.500
including Guillain-Barre
[INAUDIBLE] syndrome

01:10:22.500 --> 01:10:26.890
and also microcephaly in babies.

01:10:26.890 --> 01:10:31.660
So, the timeline is almost
like an old epidemic.

01:10:31.660 --> 01:10:37.000
Good doctors spot something
that they see that's not usual.

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:40.840
They contact health
authorities, there's

01:10:40.840 --> 01:10:43.690
something very
important going on.

01:10:43.690 --> 01:10:50.180
And in November 2015, the
Brazilian Ministry of Health

01:10:50.180 --> 01:10:55.300
declared a situation of national
public health emergency.

01:10:55.300 --> 01:10:58.950
We saw very few evidence.

01:10:58.950 --> 01:11:05.490
We just have short evidence,
some cases, some stillbirths

01:11:05.490 --> 01:11:08.030
with virus in their brain.

01:11:08.030 --> 01:11:11.430
But there was a no
epidemiological study

01:11:11.430 --> 01:11:12.990
to think about causality.

01:11:12.990 --> 01:11:16.140
Causality is very important
for us epidemiologists.

01:11:16.140 --> 01:11:18.250
It's a very serious business.

01:11:18.250 --> 01:11:26.670
So, what I want to say is
that the emergency in Brazil

01:11:26.670 --> 01:11:30.510
was a turning point for
the public health response.

01:11:30.510 --> 01:11:32.970
It really was a turning point.

01:11:32.970 --> 01:11:37.860
Researchers and health care
workers working together,

01:11:37.860 --> 01:11:41.250
they developed new protocols
and research instruments

01:11:41.250 --> 01:11:42.930
for field work.

01:11:42.930 --> 01:11:45.420
The magnitude of the
event to put attention

01:11:45.420 --> 01:11:47.670
on this [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:47.670 --> 01:11:51.390
I mean, it was so
important that broke

01:11:51.390 --> 01:11:54.490
personal and
institutional barriers,

01:11:54.490 --> 01:11:59.430
creating a collective
solidarity feeling, a commitment

01:11:59.430 --> 01:12:02.550
of sharing data and knowledge.

01:12:02.550 --> 01:12:04.110
That was the status.

01:12:04.110 --> 01:12:07.680
Nobody wanted to publish a
paper first like said before.

01:12:07.680 --> 01:12:09.270
We want to have a group.

01:12:09.270 --> 01:12:13.650
We want to be known as a group
that just could do things

01:12:13.650 --> 01:12:16.890
as a group, as a team,
independently in which

01:12:16.890 --> 01:12:18.520
institution [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:18.520 --> 01:12:22.300
So, I think here that I have to
say the intense collaboration

01:12:22.300 --> 01:12:28.070
of several institutions around
the world and within Brazil.

01:12:28.070 --> 01:12:32.840
And this morning, I had some
very nice thoughts like,

01:12:32.840 --> 01:12:35.720
epidemiology is a sign of
[INAUDIBLE] public health.

01:12:35.720 --> 01:12:37.820
And I fully agree.

01:12:37.820 --> 01:12:42.770
And that's what we saw on the
field exactly where we were,

01:12:42.770 --> 01:12:46.970
trying to do good
epidemiology in the situation.

01:12:46.970 --> 01:12:49.370
And I always learn
a term-- yesterday,

01:12:49.370 --> 01:12:51.680
a terminology that
I found it very

01:12:51.680 --> 01:12:53.650
appropriate for this moment.

01:12:53.650 --> 01:12:57.150
We were not doing
peacetime research.

01:12:57.150 --> 01:12:59.900
We were doing wartime research.

01:12:59.900 --> 01:13:02.600
So time was so important.

01:13:02.600 --> 01:13:05.360
Collaboration was so important.

01:13:05.360 --> 01:13:09.290
So I wanted to just briefly
to show that was the features.

01:13:09.290 --> 01:13:11.400
We had almost like a phenotype.

01:13:11.400 --> 01:13:13.120
I can't go into details.

01:13:13.120 --> 01:13:16.430
But you can see the
disproportional face

01:13:16.430 --> 01:13:17.540
and how bad--

01:13:17.540 --> 01:13:22.400
how small these children,
and how bad it was.

01:13:22.400 --> 01:13:26.720
Here, you can see the
tomography of these children,

01:13:26.720 --> 01:13:31.490
it's so easy to see the
calcification and the damage

01:13:31.490 --> 01:13:34.460
of the brain and how
important and how

01:13:34.460 --> 01:13:38.000
would be the developing of
these children considering

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:39.350
this situation.

01:13:39.350 --> 01:13:41.480
So we entered this--

01:13:41.480 --> 01:13:44.780
the Ministry of Health
proposed for the group--

01:13:44.780 --> 01:13:49.715
for our group to design
and do a case-control study

01:13:49.715 --> 01:13:54.230
that was funded by the Brazilian
Ministry of Health and Pan

01:13:54.230 --> 01:13:56.270
American Health Organization.

01:13:56.270 --> 01:13:59.360
The idea is that
epidemiologists,

01:13:59.360 --> 01:14:03.680
in our toolbox, we have
the case control as one

01:14:03.680 --> 01:14:09.700
of the first options because
we can get from the outcome

01:14:09.700 --> 01:14:10.930
to the exposure.

01:14:10.930 --> 01:14:15.410
It means almost doing
like research in reverse.

01:14:15.410 --> 01:14:18.080
You don't expect
things to happen.

01:14:18.080 --> 01:14:22.220
But you just go from
back to going to--

01:14:22.220 --> 01:14:22.900
next page.

01:14:22.900 --> 01:14:25.450
So we had many hypotheses.

01:14:25.450 --> 01:14:29.380
And two of these
hypotheses were very--

01:14:29.380 --> 01:14:35.140
let's see-- very important
considering public health.

01:14:35.140 --> 01:14:38.530
One was that a larvicide
that the government had

01:14:38.530 --> 01:14:42.910
put in the tank water that
was called pyriproxyfen

01:14:42.910 --> 01:14:45.700
was the cause of
the microcephaly.

01:14:45.700 --> 01:14:47.920
So this was a very
important issue

01:14:47.920 --> 01:14:49.990
because during an
epidemic, you would

01:14:49.990 --> 01:14:53.320
have to take out
the control measure

01:14:53.320 --> 01:14:58.150
because it was supposed to be
the cause of the microcephaly.

01:14:58.150 --> 01:15:02.620
And the other very important
[INAUDIBLE] hypothesis

01:15:02.620 --> 01:15:05.890
that came about
was about vaccine.

01:15:05.890 --> 01:15:11.110
So it got really in the media
that vaccine, like the rubella

01:15:11.110 --> 01:15:16.630
vaccine, was something
that was doing again--

01:15:16.630 --> 01:15:20.920
kind of having an epitome.

01:15:20.920 --> 01:15:26.410
Like, say, we have an outbreak
due to the vaccination.

01:15:26.410 --> 01:15:29.380
So you can imagine
what the panic

01:15:29.380 --> 01:15:32.300
and the what the amount
of confusion and rumor

01:15:32.300 --> 01:15:33.670
that was going on.

01:15:33.670 --> 01:15:36.820
So those pipe waters
had to be tested.

01:15:36.820 --> 01:15:43.900
Of course, our main hypothesis
was really the Zika virus

01:15:43.900 --> 01:15:45.011
infection.

01:15:45.011 --> 01:15:45.510
Why?

01:15:45.510 --> 01:15:51.310
Because it had been proven to
be very neurotrophic in animals,

01:15:51.310 --> 01:15:55.400
we had the right temporal
sequence, and so on.

01:15:55.400 --> 01:15:58.450
So we designed a
case-control study

01:15:58.450 --> 01:16:01.450
that was the first
case-control study we designed.

01:16:01.450 --> 01:16:04.480
We couldn't get
retrospective [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:04.480 --> 01:16:09.760
because we had to be sure that
they were congenitally infected

01:16:09.760 --> 01:16:12.220
and we choose the
right controls.

01:16:12.220 --> 01:16:15.370
And laboratory confirmation--
it just brought it here

01:16:15.370 --> 01:16:17.600
because it was so important.

01:16:17.600 --> 01:16:20.050
We didn't have good lab tests.

01:16:20.050 --> 01:16:22.960
We still don't have
a good lab test.

01:16:22.960 --> 01:16:29.380
And what do I mean is that
Zika and dengue, being

01:16:29.380 --> 01:16:33.610
from the same virus,
like the same flavivirus,

01:16:33.610 --> 01:16:35.200
they cross-react.

01:16:35.200 --> 01:16:39.700
So remember that this population
had been exposed to virus

01:16:39.700 --> 01:16:41.860
for 30 years for dengue.

01:16:41.860 --> 01:16:44.630
So when you get a positive
serological result,

01:16:44.630 --> 01:16:47.830
you don't know if it
was dengue or not.

01:16:47.830 --> 01:16:51.010
But we are very lucky to
have in our institutions--

01:16:51.010 --> 01:16:53.020
like you said before--

01:16:53.020 --> 01:16:55.600
preparedness, like
with this lab,

01:16:55.600 --> 01:16:59.290
it was a reference
lab for flavivirus,

01:16:59.290 --> 01:17:03.970
and could do more lab
[INAUDIBLE] tests like PRNT

01:17:03.970 --> 01:17:06.910
Just for Zika and
for dengue in order

01:17:06.910 --> 01:17:10.900
to know for sure if we're
having a Zika-positive case

01:17:10.900 --> 01:17:12.940
or a dengue-positive case.

01:17:12.940 --> 01:17:16.870
I'm just going to show
that these factors--

01:17:16.870 --> 01:17:20.320
I just made a big jump and I
excuse the epidemiologists.

01:17:20.320 --> 01:17:24.580
So you can see the odds one
doesn't have any difference

01:17:24.580 --> 01:17:26.810
between cases and controls.

01:17:26.810 --> 01:17:31.870
So you can see here
smoking was a confounder--

01:17:31.870 --> 01:17:33.550
actually was a confounder.

01:17:33.550 --> 01:17:36.490
Alcohol, vaccine,
and larvicide had

01:17:36.490 --> 01:17:40.160
nothing to do with
this epidemic at least.

01:17:40.160 --> 01:17:42.760
And when we have
this cartoon here,

01:17:42.760 --> 01:17:45.100
what we see in
this case-control--

01:17:45.100 --> 01:17:50.200
it's something very strong,
a very, very powerful

01:17:50.200 --> 01:17:55.930
association-- only
cases had been infected

01:17:55.930 --> 01:18:00.000
or had been congenitally
infected with microcephaly.

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:03.880
So we're talking about in that
day's epidemic of microcephaly

01:18:03.880 --> 01:18:05.940
and not all microcephalies.

01:18:05.940 --> 01:18:10.840
And another very important
result from this case-control

01:18:10.840 --> 01:18:11.740
study--

01:18:11.740 --> 01:18:18.580
then we measured the past
exposure of this Zika

01:18:18.580 --> 01:18:21.280
in the mothers of
control that will be

01:18:21.280 --> 01:18:24.430
kind of our population control.

01:18:24.430 --> 01:18:27.590
Even if it's not such
a large sample size,

01:18:27.590 --> 01:18:31.330
60% of these mothers
had been exposed.

01:18:31.330 --> 01:18:32.780
What does it mean?

01:18:32.780 --> 01:18:36.700
It means that in the
first wave of Zika virus,

01:18:36.700 --> 01:18:39.340
there was these huge exposures.

01:18:39.340 --> 01:18:45.310
I mean, we did have a naive
population, a huge population,

01:18:45.310 --> 01:18:49.750
that were struck by
this wave of Zika

01:18:49.750 --> 01:18:54.100
and become infected
and were infected

01:18:54.100 --> 01:18:56.540
and had an antibody response.

01:18:56.540 --> 01:18:58.930
So those are published papers.

01:18:58.930 --> 01:19:05.810
The ones who work in research
know this is very fast.

01:19:05.810 --> 01:19:08.920
I mean, we did it in
a fast-track approval

01:19:08.920 --> 01:19:11.480
that went under the emergency.

01:19:11.480 --> 01:19:14.360
And so, that's
the situation now.

01:19:14.360 --> 01:19:15.800
And what now?

01:19:15.800 --> 01:19:19.280
You'll see the first map
shows the first wave.

01:19:19.280 --> 01:19:24.140
When you see the first,
very focused point,

01:19:24.140 --> 01:19:29.840
the epitome just in the first
in the northeast in two very

01:19:29.840 --> 01:19:32.240
spots in the south.

01:19:32.240 --> 01:19:35.450
And later on in
the next year, you

01:19:35.450 --> 01:19:38.300
can see that it's not
too much transmission.

01:19:38.300 --> 01:19:41.420
It doesn't look like
too much transmission.

01:19:41.420 --> 01:19:44.180
If we think about
surveillance, we just

01:19:44.180 --> 01:19:48.470
have surveillance data for 2016.

01:19:48.470 --> 01:19:52.280
That's the red line that
means the Zika infection.

01:19:52.280 --> 01:19:58.370
And we can see in this pic what
we see is seasonal epidemics,

01:19:58.370 --> 01:20:00.650
and you have a flat plateau.

01:20:00.650 --> 01:20:04.530
That transmission-- we don't
see too much transmission there.

01:20:04.530 --> 01:20:06.740
Now it's chikungunya time.

01:20:06.740 --> 01:20:08.750
It's not Zika time anymore.

01:20:08.750 --> 01:20:11.450
But what we see now--

01:20:11.450 --> 01:20:13.200
is it going?

01:20:13.200 --> 01:20:14.450
This is what I found.

01:20:14.450 --> 01:20:17.500
It was more surprising
of the epidemic

01:20:17.500 --> 01:20:21.215
was the use of WhatsApp
for good and for bad.

01:20:21.215 --> 01:20:23.150
I mean, for good,
for communication

01:20:23.150 --> 01:20:25.040
between the doctors
and patients,

01:20:25.040 --> 01:20:28.310
and for bad, for
rumors, for fake news,

01:20:28.310 --> 01:20:30.240
for everything you can imagine.

01:20:30.240 --> 01:20:33.630
So this was kind of a nightmare.

01:20:33.630 --> 01:20:37.040
So, just brief remarks here.

01:20:37.040 --> 01:20:38.960
What were the challenges?

01:20:38.960 --> 01:20:43.130
I think there are now ongoing
cohorts all over the world

01:20:43.130 --> 01:20:46.880
monitoring pregnant
women and newborn babies.

01:20:46.880 --> 01:20:49.940
We know very little
about the risks.

01:20:49.940 --> 01:20:54.440
I mean, if the risk is a
stable or we have varying risks

01:20:54.440 --> 01:20:56.870
according to
different populations.

01:20:56.870 --> 01:21:00.890
We don't know very little about
this fraction of the disease

01:21:00.890 --> 01:21:02.090
we're talking about.

01:21:02.090 --> 01:21:06.290
We don't know how these
children are going to develop.

01:21:06.290 --> 01:21:07.740
There are a lot--

01:21:07.740 --> 01:21:10.510
there's much, much
room to improve

01:21:10.510 --> 01:21:14.540
in diagnostics for management
and also for research.

01:21:14.540 --> 01:21:18.440
I think that we are in a point
that we really need improvement

01:21:18.440 --> 01:21:20.720
in this kind of diagnosis.

01:21:20.720 --> 01:21:25.700
And there are other
very important research

01:21:25.700 --> 01:21:27.770
being carried on.

01:21:27.770 --> 01:21:31.880
Now, I want really to
thank our group here

01:21:31.880 --> 01:21:33.380
and to present our group.

01:21:33.380 --> 01:21:36.620
That's Microcephaly
Epidemic Research Groups.

01:21:36.620 --> 01:21:40.550
I mean, a lot of people
from many institutions,

01:21:40.550 --> 01:21:44.490
many public institutions,
from all over the world,

01:21:44.490 --> 01:21:46.370
and especially from Brazil.

01:21:46.370 --> 01:21:49.070
A special thanks to
Dr. Laura Rodrigues

01:21:49.070 --> 01:21:52.490
from London School of Hygiene
and Tropical Medicine.

01:21:52.490 --> 01:21:54.800
And here are all
the institutions.

01:21:54.800 --> 01:22:01.195
And here are all
of our supporters--

01:22:01.195 --> 01:22:05.640
NIH, there is a cohort of
pregnant women with NIH

01:22:05.640 --> 01:22:10.110
and a lot to work with
ZikaPLAN in many fields.

01:22:10.110 --> 01:22:11.935
Thank you very much
for your attention.

01:22:11.935 --> 01:22:15.895
[APPLAUSE]

01:22:21.850 --> 01:22:27.510
- OK, so we're going to have
just a brief discussion.

01:22:27.510 --> 01:22:30.470
And then we're going to open
the floor for questions.

01:22:30.470 --> 01:22:32.830
So please start thinking
about your question

01:22:32.830 --> 01:22:36.190
because we're going to need
your participation in a moment.

01:22:36.190 --> 01:22:39.340
So, I think there are
sort of three things that

01:22:39.340 --> 01:22:42.510
became pretty obvious across
the three presentations.

01:22:42.510 --> 01:22:46.300
One is really the importance
of local capacity.

01:22:46.300 --> 01:22:48.280
That's absolutely crucial.

01:22:48.280 --> 01:22:50.740
And it's not that we are
solving all the problems

01:22:50.740 --> 01:22:54.130
for the next outbreak, but as
you build up the local capacity

01:22:54.130 --> 01:22:56.230
to respond, to
have the knowledge,

01:22:56.230 --> 01:22:59.860
to have the tools, that's
absolutely crucial.

01:22:59.860 --> 01:23:04.840
The second one is each one
of this work is basically

01:23:04.840 --> 01:23:07.400
about overcoming challenges.

01:23:07.400 --> 01:23:08.620
And they are many.

01:23:08.620 --> 01:23:12.070
either because everybody tells
you you can't work in the DRC

01:23:12.070 --> 01:23:14.080
or because you are in
the middle of an outbreak

01:23:14.080 --> 01:23:18.730
when nobody knows what to do,
but you have to do something.

01:23:18.730 --> 01:23:20.590
And I think, to me, the
most important thing

01:23:20.590 --> 01:23:21.650
that comes across--

01:23:21.650 --> 01:23:24.700
and fortunately, this
is true for many of us--

01:23:24.700 --> 01:23:27.640
is that if you really want to
do the right thing in the middle

01:23:27.640 --> 01:23:31.330
of an outbreak, you really have
to go against the brutal tenure

01:23:31.330 --> 01:23:35.420
system and focus about saving
lives and not writing papers.

01:23:35.420 --> 01:23:36.730
And this is crucial.

01:23:36.730 --> 01:23:38.140
And some of us do that.

01:23:38.140 --> 01:23:39.484
We may get--

01:23:39.484 --> 01:23:40.900
I'm not saying
what I'm going to--

01:23:40.900 --> 01:23:41.400
anyway.

01:23:41.400 --> 01:23:42.340
[LAUGHTER]

01:23:42.340 --> 01:23:44.380
We may not be very
successful at the end,

01:23:44.380 --> 01:23:46.930
but at least we can
sleep well at night

01:23:46.930 --> 01:23:48.630
with our head on the
pillow because we

01:23:48.630 --> 01:23:51.640
are trying to save lives, not
to get a paper in [INAUDIBLE]..

01:23:51.640 --> 01:23:52.430
This is crucial.

01:23:52.430 --> 01:23:57.280
And I cannot thank you
enough for bringing that up.

01:23:57.280 --> 01:24:00.580
So, I'm just going to have
one question for each speaker

01:24:00.580 --> 01:24:02.020
just to warm us
up, and then we're

01:24:02.020 --> 01:24:03.145
going to open to the floor.

01:24:03.145 --> 01:24:06.430
So, Happi, I want to
ask you a question.

01:24:06.430 --> 01:24:07.480
You do all this training.

01:24:07.480 --> 01:24:10.600
You have people coming from
all those different countries.

01:24:10.600 --> 01:24:14.530
Training there, training here
and abroad, then those people

01:24:14.530 --> 01:24:15.830
go back to their countries.

01:24:15.830 --> 01:24:18.430
You can guarantee
what goes to Nigeria.

01:24:18.430 --> 01:24:22.180
Are they able to actually build
the same kind of infrastructure

01:24:22.180 --> 01:24:24.700
and have the same
kind of response

01:24:24.700 --> 01:24:27.560
fast as you can
provide in Nigeria?

01:24:27.560 --> 01:24:30.730
So, is this training
that you're providing

01:24:30.730 --> 01:24:34.810
being translated into really
resources in the countries

01:24:34.810 --> 01:24:36.632
when they go back?

01:24:36.632 --> 01:24:40.690
Anne, I wonder if
you've found something

01:24:40.690 --> 01:24:43.050
on sort of the social side.

01:24:43.050 --> 01:24:44.410
So how about stigma?

01:24:44.410 --> 01:24:47.470
How about social consequences
in the lives of those people?

01:24:47.470 --> 01:24:49.450
And many of them
have been surviving

01:24:49.450 --> 01:24:50.840
for more than four years.

01:24:50.840 --> 01:24:54.140
So were you able to learn
something about this?

01:24:54.140 --> 01:24:55.630
And one thing that
got me curious

01:24:55.630 --> 01:24:59.890
is, do we know anything if
the asymptomatic infections--

01:24:59.890 --> 01:25:01.810
if those people are infectious?

01:25:01.810 --> 01:25:04.840
Because if we do have
so many transmission

01:25:04.840 --> 01:25:07.660
is still going on although
everybody think it's over,

01:25:07.660 --> 01:25:10.590
why don't we have
another outbreak?

01:25:10.590 --> 01:25:14.140
And Celina, I'm kind of
going to put you on the spot,

01:25:14.140 --> 01:25:16.660
but we are both Brazilian
so I think I can do that.

01:25:16.660 --> 01:25:17.620
- Friendly fire.

01:25:17.620 --> 01:25:19.220
[LAUGHTER]

01:25:19.220 --> 01:25:22.090
- So, I think another
thing that is obvious

01:25:22.090 --> 01:25:24.840
is context matters always.

01:25:24.840 --> 01:25:27.100
We are never going to
have two outbreaks that

01:25:27.100 --> 01:25:30.610
are going to be the same in the
way they happen and in the way

01:25:30.610 --> 01:25:32.390
we respond to them.

01:25:32.390 --> 01:25:34.450
So, I think you
highlighted the importance

01:25:34.450 --> 01:25:38.020
of the front-line workers,
of the government declaring

01:25:38.020 --> 01:25:41.110
an emergency even not
with so much evidence,

01:25:41.110 --> 01:25:44.620
but he did, and
in supporting you

01:25:44.620 --> 01:25:48.900
to lead this incredible work,
this epidemiological work,

01:25:48.900 --> 01:25:50.740
to respond to the epidemic.

01:25:50.740 --> 01:25:54.640
The context now, 2017,
is very different.

01:25:54.640 --> 01:25:57.850
The leadership, both in the
government and in the ministry

01:25:57.850 --> 01:25:58.840
is different.

01:25:58.840 --> 01:26:04.460
So I would like you to reflect
how this whole crisis would

01:26:04.460 --> 01:26:07.840
unfold if Zika had
arrived in Brazil not

01:26:07.840 --> 01:26:10.754
in 2015, but in 2017.

01:26:10.754 --> 01:26:12.670
I told you I was going
to put you on the spot.

01:26:12.670 --> 01:26:14.950
[LAUGHTER]

01:26:14.950 --> 01:26:15.980
So, Christian.

01:26:15.980 --> 01:26:18.470
- All right.

01:26:18.470 --> 01:26:19.394
I don't--

01:26:19.394 --> 01:26:22.970
- Oh, you have your
microphone, so go for it.

01:26:22.970 --> 01:26:23.680
- Yeah.

01:26:23.680 --> 01:26:26.570
I think one of the
questions was are there

01:26:26.570 --> 01:26:30.590
facilities for trainees
to use after training

01:26:30.590 --> 01:26:35.330
so that they can respond as fast
as we did in Nigeria in 2014?

01:26:35.330 --> 01:26:37.010
The answer is yes.

01:26:37.010 --> 01:26:39.560
In [INAUDIBLE],,
you saw we ensured

01:26:39.560 --> 01:26:42.925
that the trainees actually
get back and use facilities.

01:26:42.925 --> 01:26:45.050
So one thing that we did
basically in the countries

01:26:45.050 --> 01:26:48.310
where we have this [INAUDIBLE]
network across a region.

01:26:48.310 --> 01:26:51.500
We've set up a
reference laboratory

01:26:51.500 --> 01:26:54.080
with state-of-art
facility, for instance.

01:26:54.080 --> 01:26:56.750
In Nigeria, we have
next-generation sequences

01:26:56.750 --> 01:26:57.320
installed.

01:26:57.320 --> 01:26:58.945
We have the same in
Sierra Leone and we

01:26:58.945 --> 01:27:02.450
have the same in Senegal.

01:27:02.450 --> 01:27:04.965
And those operating
those systems

01:27:04.965 --> 01:27:06.090
received the same training.

01:27:06.090 --> 01:27:10.190
And we use the same protocol
for any eventuality.

01:27:10.190 --> 01:27:13.250
So [INAUDIBLE] apart from
using those high-end equipment,

01:27:13.250 --> 01:27:17.750
we've also translated this
into middle-end and low-end

01:27:17.750 --> 01:27:19.380
facilities that it can use.

01:27:19.380 --> 01:27:22.180
For instance, for the
rapid diagnostic tests,

01:27:22.180 --> 01:27:26.240
we've done extensive training
for high-tech workers that

01:27:26.240 --> 01:27:28.416
can use those for diagnosis.

01:27:28.416 --> 01:27:30.040
And we also have the
medial [INAUDIBLE]

01:27:30.040 --> 01:27:31.940
that can use that
qPCR for diagnosis,

01:27:31.940 --> 01:27:33.470
for confirmational purposes.

01:27:33.470 --> 01:27:35.350
And in [INAUDIBLE],, for
instance, or Nigeria

01:27:35.350 --> 01:27:39.570
or in Dakar, you'll see
the very high-end equipment

01:27:39.570 --> 01:27:41.362
where we can actually
do confirmation.

01:27:41.362 --> 01:27:43.070
And that is the reason
why, for instance,

01:27:43.070 --> 01:27:44.810
because we have that--

01:27:44.810 --> 01:27:49.150
we've had cases in [INAUDIBLE]
suspected cases of Lassa fever

01:27:49.150 --> 01:27:50.740
in [INAUDIBLE] weeks back.

01:27:50.740 --> 01:27:53.920
Those were sent to those
facilities in Senegal.

01:27:53.920 --> 01:27:56.370
And actually, we confirm
it wasn't Lassa fever.

01:27:56.370 --> 01:27:59.640
Presently in my lab, we're
dealing with monkeypox outbreak

01:27:59.640 --> 01:28:00.590
in Nigeria.

01:28:00.590 --> 01:28:02.930
So, and we're basically
confirming cases

01:28:02.930 --> 01:28:04.880
and also responding
to the outbreak

01:28:04.880 --> 01:28:06.625
and facilitating
government intervention

01:28:06.625 --> 01:28:07.940
in all those areas.

01:28:07.940 --> 01:28:08.690
I think in a way--

01:28:08.690 --> 01:28:10.860
I think in a way, we've
kind of addressed that.

01:28:10.860 --> 01:28:14.681
And that's one of the reasons
why we're not just framing,

01:28:14.681 --> 01:28:16.930
but we're also ensuring that
there are facilities that

01:28:16.930 --> 01:28:18.060
will accompany the trainees.

01:28:18.060 --> 01:28:18.555
- Wonderful.

01:28:18.555 --> 01:28:19.055
Thank you.

01:28:19.055 --> 01:28:20.414
Anne?

01:28:20.414 --> 01:28:22.513
- OK, so you asked me
two different questions.

01:28:22.513 --> 01:28:23.770
Is this mic-- OK.

01:28:23.770 --> 01:28:26.282
I think this mic's on.

01:28:26.282 --> 01:28:27.990
So, you asked me two
different questions.

01:28:27.990 --> 01:28:32.810
The first one was about the
social effects of Ebola.

01:28:32.810 --> 01:28:37.170
And I just recently came
back from the 1995 outbreak.

01:28:37.170 --> 01:28:39.500
So this is something that's
very, very fresh in my mind

01:28:39.500 --> 01:28:41.390
right now.

01:28:41.390 --> 01:28:44.420
I spend a lot of
time doing interviews

01:28:44.420 --> 01:28:49.240
and talking to these people
about their experience.

01:28:49.240 --> 01:28:53.250
And I think it's very,
very interesting.

01:28:53.250 --> 01:28:56.270
First of all,
meeting these people

01:28:56.270 --> 01:28:59.810
and giving them the opportunity
to talk in this case just 22

01:28:59.810 --> 01:29:02.720
years later, it's the
first time anybody

01:29:02.720 --> 01:29:06.980
had come to them in
20 years to ask them.

01:29:06.980 --> 01:29:08.990
You know, in West Africa--
and this was a point

01:29:08.990 --> 01:29:13.730
that they made and really
was driven home to me.

01:29:13.730 --> 01:29:16.100
In West Africa
after the outbreak,

01:29:16.100 --> 01:29:19.400
there are 16,000 survivors.

01:29:19.400 --> 01:29:21.320
And so, there are
support groups.

01:29:21.320 --> 01:29:24.560
There are social services.

01:29:24.560 --> 01:29:27.500
There is a huge investment
on the part of the US

01:29:27.500 --> 01:29:31.250
and other governments to study
them, to enroll them in trials,

01:29:31.250 --> 01:29:34.250
to enroll them in studies,
which also gives them

01:29:34.250 --> 01:29:38.780
the benefit of having quality
of care, whereas people

01:29:38.780 --> 01:29:44.010
in West or in Congo,
all of these cohorts--

01:29:44.010 --> 01:29:45.196
there's nothing.

01:29:45.196 --> 01:29:46.070
There are no studies.

01:29:46.070 --> 01:29:47.450
There are no trials.

01:29:47.450 --> 01:29:49.310
There's no support.

01:29:49.310 --> 01:29:53.510
And even to go to these
sites and to do these studies

01:29:53.510 --> 01:29:56.630
in '76 and '95 outbreaks,
we needed to have labs.

01:29:56.630 --> 01:29:59.600
And we had big negotiations
with the hospitals

01:29:59.600 --> 01:30:02.810
and the local government because
they didn't want the survivors

01:30:02.810 --> 01:30:04.460
all in the same place.

01:30:04.460 --> 01:30:06.320
And they were worried
about what happens

01:30:06.320 --> 01:30:07.666
when the survivors come.

01:30:07.666 --> 01:30:10.040
And in fact, the survivors
were very nervous about coming

01:30:10.040 --> 01:30:10.706
to the hospital.

01:30:10.706 --> 01:30:15.860
They felt the issue of
stigma is so great even

01:30:15.860 --> 01:30:20.670
in trying to do
studies with them.

01:30:20.670 --> 01:30:22.740
It's something that's
very, very important.

01:30:22.740 --> 01:30:26.450
And so even just the fact of how
hard doing these studies were

01:30:26.450 --> 01:30:29.000
is all attributable to
this issue of stigma.

01:30:29.000 --> 01:30:32.540
And the stories that
still need to be

01:30:32.540 --> 01:30:34.160
understood in greater detail--

01:30:34.160 --> 01:30:37.280
and we hope to do much more
with ethnographic studies

01:30:37.280 --> 01:30:41.750
and really delving
into their experiences

01:30:41.750 --> 01:30:44.220
so it doesn't happen again.

01:30:44.220 --> 01:30:46.670
So yes, stigma is
very, very important

01:30:46.670 --> 01:30:49.977
and not explored at all.

01:30:49.977 --> 01:30:51.560
The second question
you asked me about

01:30:51.560 --> 01:30:52.970
was asymptomatic infections.

01:30:52.970 --> 01:30:55.610
And you asked a very
important question

01:30:55.610 --> 01:30:58.160
which is something that we
hoped to be able to answer,

01:30:58.160 --> 01:31:01.490
which is do people are still--
what role do these people play

01:31:01.490 --> 01:31:02.430
in transmission.

01:31:02.430 --> 01:31:04.390
And we don't know
the answer yet.

01:31:04.390 --> 01:31:05.671
But we hope to learn.

01:31:05.671 --> 01:31:06.170
- Thank you.

01:31:06.170 --> 01:31:08.180
Celina?

01:31:08.180 --> 01:31:14.630
- Well, you asked me a
very difficult question

01:31:14.630 --> 01:31:16.640
because prediction
what's going--

01:31:16.640 --> 01:31:20.450
what could have happened if you
have a different government.

01:31:20.450 --> 01:31:23.900
But it gives me the
opportunity to say

01:31:23.900 --> 01:31:28.070
that when the Zika
epidemic started,

01:31:28.070 --> 01:31:34.160
we were in an intense
economic and political crisis.

01:31:34.160 --> 01:31:36.200
I don't know if you remember.

01:31:36.200 --> 01:31:39.500
It was under Dilma
Rousseff's impeachment.

01:31:39.500 --> 01:31:42.320
So it was right to--

01:31:42.320 --> 01:31:47.510
and of a period and
starting a new government.

01:31:47.510 --> 01:31:55.100
And at that time, it was such in
intense scientist mobilization.

01:31:55.100 --> 01:31:58.430
I mean, we were asked
to write reports

01:31:58.430 --> 01:32:03.890
and to look and go to the front
line to see what was going on.

01:32:03.890 --> 01:32:06.380
So it just got to
the point that I

01:32:06.380 --> 01:32:10.380
think the scientists
influence when they can.

01:32:10.380 --> 01:32:13.250
And when the situation--

01:32:13.250 --> 01:32:15.020
to take responsibility.

01:32:15.020 --> 01:32:16.730
There is nothing
that you can call

01:32:16.730 --> 01:32:18.950
for in a situation like this.

01:32:18.950 --> 01:32:22.620
But I think we must be concerned
about the next government

01:32:22.620 --> 01:32:26.620
that's cutting the
public health--

01:32:26.620 --> 01:32:29.870
I mean, support and
research funding.

01:32:29.870 --> 01:32:32.930
So we must be concerned
because we're just

01:32:32.930 --> 01:32:37.490
starting to understand
the full development

01:32:37.490 --> 01:32:42.210
and the full spectrum
of the disease now.

01:32:42.210 --> 01:32:47.150
And I don't think that we could
say that transmissions stopped

01:32:47.150 --> 01:32:49.980
and it shouldn't worry
about it any longer.

01:32:49.980 --> 01:32:55.400
I think we must watch out
because arbovirus epidemiology

01:32:55.400 --> 01:33:00.380
arbovirus is changing,
and is changing fast.

01:33:00.380 --> 01:33:04.500
So, the first maps
we saw in the world,

01:33:04.500 --> 01:33:07.850
we just have the tropical
areas saying the vector-borne

01:33:07.850 --> 01:33:09.620
with population.

01:33:09.620 --> 01:33:11.360
Now it's much wider.

01:33:11.360 --> 01:33:15.380
I mean, we have different
things, which just give me

01:33:15.380 --> 01:33:21.350
the opportunity also to see what
range of intervention actions

01:33:21.350 --> 01:33:24.770
were proposed since the
first, and were very

01:33:24.770 --> 01:33:27.200
hard to keep for a long time.

01:33:27.200 --> 01:33:30.800
The range of interventions
for the epidemic

01:33:30.800 --> 01:33:38.570
was mosquito control strategies,
postponing pregnancy,

01:33:38.570 --> 01:33:42.530
travels recommendations,
safe sex, and so on.

01:33:42.530 --> 01:33:45.080
So, you really need
to build knowledge

01:33:45.080 --> 01:33:49.710
to make these recommendations
in long term possible.

01:33:49.710 --> 01:33:53.600
So thank you for giving me
this opportunity to complete.

01:33:53.600 --> 01:33:55.040
