01:36:27.877 --> 01:36:28.460
- That's fine.

01:36:28.460 --> 01:36:30.150
- My name is
[? Gladiver ?] Santiago.

01:36:30.150 --> 01:36:30.650
- Thank you.

01:36:30.650 --> 01:36:31.376
- OK.

01:36:31.376 --> 01:36:33.250
- All right, so Christian,
you want to start?

01:36:33.250 --> 01:36:34.070
- OK.

01:36:34.070 --> 01:36:38.910
Yeah, the question is
what was the difference

01:36:38.910 --> 01:36:46.640
between the Nigeria and the
Guinea experience in terms

01:36:46.640 --> 01:36:48.950
of Ebola response.

01:36:48.950 --> 01:36:51.630
Well, there are
two major things.

01:36:51.630 --> 01:36:55.470
One was yes, we understand
that in the case of--

01:36:55.470 --> 01:36:58.320
I mean, infrastructure was one.

01:36:58.320 --> 01:37:03.120
But then I think what I
saw there as most important

01:37:03.120 --> 01:37:08.980
in that was in the case of
Nigeria, there were two things.

01:37:08.980 --> 01:37:12.970
One was probably an element
of luck in the sense

01:37:12.970 --> 01:37:17.570
that when the [INAUDIBLE]
case arrived at the airport

01:37:17.570 --> 01:37:24.000
in Lagos, he was already sick
and he stumbled at the airport.

01:37:24.000 --> 01:37:27.540
Then at that moment and at that
time, he was probably a VIP.

01:37:27.540 --> 01:37:31.370
He was taken to one of the
best hospitals in Nigeria.

01:37:31.370 --> 01:37:32.990
It also happened
that at that time,

01:37:32.990 --> 01:37:34.770
the health sector
in Nigeria was--

01:37:34.770 --> 01:37:37.810
public sector was paralyzed
because the doctors

01:37:37.810 --> 01:37:39.990
were on strike.

01:37:39.990 --> 01:37:43.870
So he had no choice but to
go to a private hospital.

01:37:43.870 --> 01:37:45.930
And he received treatment there.

01:37:45.930 --> 01:37:51.600
But the difference
though, is the fact

01:37:51.600 --> 01:37:53.280
that in Nigeria,
we had that ability

01:37:53.280 --> 01:37:55.260
to diagnose on the ground.

01:37:55.260 --> 01:37:57.040
In Guinea, it was
the other way around.

01:37:57.040 --> 01:38:01.740
In Guinea, the samples
were from over to France

01:38:01.740 --> 01:38:05.460
and diagnosed in France
and result turned down

01:38:05.460 --> 01:38:06.900
to Conakry, and
then from Conakry

01:38:06.900 --> 01:38:09.040
down to the
confinements of Guinea.

01:38:09.040 --> 01:38:12.720
And that on the average,
was taking 10 to 14 days.

01:38:12.720 --> 01:38:16.980
So within that period, then
the disease was spreading.

01:38:16.980 --> 01:38:21.990
But in the case of Nigeria, we
had all that it took on-site.

01:38:21.990 --> 01:38:28.730
But then most importantly,
it was self-reliance.

01:38:28.730 --> 01:38:31.740
The Nigerian health authority
believed in themselves,

01:38:31.740 --> 01:38:33.730
unlike happened in
Guinea, where they

01:38:33.730 --> 01:38:36.700
were pretty much dictated upon.

01:38:36.700 --> 01:38:38.560
In Nigeria, for
instance, when we

01:38:38.560 --> 01:38:43.150
did our diagnosis and many of
the international organizations

01:38:43.150 --> 01:38:47.430
came in with their
views and their opinions

01:38:47.430 --> 01:38:51.330
with their suggestion that
they need to confirm first

01:38:51.330 --> 01:38:57.080
before we decide what to
do, the Nigerian government

01:38:57.080 --> 01:39:00.800
told them we do things
the way we want.

01:39:00.800 --> 01:39:03.350
And that was a major
game changer because

01:39:03.350 --> 01:39:05.600
for a long time, if you
went to WHO website,

01:39:05.600 --> 01:39:07.970
it was still unconfirmed.

01:39:07.970 --> 01:39:09.800
But if you were
going by WHO rule,

01:39:09.800 --> 01:39:11.730
we'd have been in big trouble.

01:39:11.730 --> 01:39:13.760
So we're very,
very self-reliant,

01:39:13.760 --> 01:39:15.900
very confident about
what we're doing.

01:39:15.900 --> 01:39:18.950
And we went and then
took the bull by the horn

01:39:18.950 --> 01:39:21.410
and addressed those
things immediately.

01:39:21.410 --> 01:39:23.030
And eventually we
were vindicated.

01:39:23.030 --> 01:39:24.162
Thank you.

01:39:24.162 --> 01:39:24.994
- Anne?

01:39:24.994 --> 01:39:26.600
- Thank you.

01:39:26.600 --> 01:39:28.160
So, the question
that you asked was

01:39:28.160 --> 01:39:33.320
about what do we know about
long-term sequelae in family

01:39:33.320 --> 01:39:37.370
members, in health care
workers, and what do we

01:39:37.370 --> 01:39:39.980
know about transmission,
essentially.

01:39:39.980 --> 01:39:43.850
And the answer is not much yet.

01:39:43.850 --> 01:39:45.890
And I hope you're
on my study section

01:39:45.890 --> 01:39:51.680
for the grant I've submitted
to be able to really understand

01:39:51.680 --> 01:39:53.900
in greater detail about this.

01:39:53.900 --> 01:39:57.140
You know, one of
the big issues is

01:39:57.140 --> 01:40:01.850
when you talk about asymptomatic
infection is what does that

01:40:01.850 --> 01:40:02.360
really mean?

01:40:02.360 --> 01:40:04.610
I mean, asymptomatic
infection means

01:40:04.610 --> 01:40:07.039
that we've found that
there were seroreactive.

01:40:07.039 --> 01:40:09.580
But one of the questions that
we did ask these people as well

01:40:09.580 --> 01:40:11.630
is, did you have signs
or symptoms of anything

01:40:11.630 --> 01:40:15.245
during that time period
or at any point later?

01:40:15.245 --> 01:40:16.870
Some people would
remember some things.

01:40:16.870 --> 01:40:18.540
Some people might not.

01:40:18.540 --> 01:40:21.110
And so the question is, were
they symptomatically infected?

01:40:21.110 --> 01:40:24.092
Did they truly
not have symptoms,

01:40:24.092 --> 01:40:25.550
or were they
minimally symptomatic,

01:40:25.550 --> 01:40:27.508
or was it just something
that was unrecognized?

01:40:27.508 --> 01:40:30.030
Because what we now know
about the Ebola outbreak

01:40:30.030 --> 01:40:32.780
or about Ebola as a disease
is that it can manifest itself

01:40:32.780 --> 01:40:34.710
in a variety of ways.

01:40:34.710 --> 01:40:41.950
It's not just the apocalyptic,
hemorrhagic version that

01:40:41.950 --> 01:40:43.820
has been so well publicized.

01:40:43.820 --> 01:40:46.230
So there's a lot to
understand, first of all,

01:40:46.230 --> 01:40:49.790
whether or not people actually
were symptomatic, minimally

01:40:49.790 --> 01:40:51.950
symptomatic, asymptomatic,
or unrecognized,

01:40:51.950 --> 01:40:53.912
and then what that will mean.

01:40:53.912 --> 01:40:55.370
- Celina?

01:40:55.370 --> 01:41:03.570
- OK, I was just about improved
ability of seeing or detecting

01:41:03.570 --> 01:41:05.890
an outbreak.

01:41:05.890 --> 01:41:10.415
If you think about very
urbanized places that

01:41:10.415 --> 01:41:13.440
were environmental,
in Brazil, we

01:41:13.440 --> 01:41:17.140
do have quite a
public health system,

01:41:17.140 --> 01:41:24.500
and with family practitioners
and there was a structure.

01:41:24.500 --> 01:41:30.400
So if you have those people
at the front line, well aware

01:41:30.400 --> 01:41:34.210
and knowing that if
they report something,

01:41:34.210 --> 01:41:35.350
it's going to be looked--

01:41:35.350 --> 01:41:38.540
[INAUDIBLE] something that's
going to be investigated.

01:41:38.540 --> 01:41:40.510
I think that's the
beginning of everything

01:41:40.510 --> 01:41:42.850
of what community approach.

01:41:42.850 --> 01:41:47.800
Maybe there are some now with
big data or things like this.

01:41:47.800 --> 01:41:50.680
I think I'm going to
join your section just

01:41:50.680 --> 01:41:53.500
to see what you're
going to say about it.

01:41:53.500 --> 01:41:55.990
But normally, what
we tend to see

01:41:55.990 --> 01:42:00.180
is the patient when he
comes to, and someone just

01:42:00.180 --> 01:42:04.360
spots that something different
or unusual in large numbers,

01:42:04.360 --> 01:42:05.560
or whatever.

01:42:05.560 --> 01:42:09.460
So, I feel that training and
having good house workers

01:42:09.460 --> 01:42:11.470
and good community support--

01:42:11.470 --> 01:42:14.770
all those things
are essential for--

01:42:14.770 --> 01:42:18.820
I mean, if we can
improve this ability

01:42:18.820 --> 01:42:23.690
to see the outbreaks
in a shorter time.

01:42:23.690 --> 01:42:26.290
- Universal health care, primary
health care, the backbone

01:42:26.290 --> 01:42:28.090
of the SDGs?

01:42:28.090 --> 01:42:32.360
So, let's get two or
three more questions.

01:42:32.360 --> 01:42:35.260
- Hi, I'm John [? Rigero. ?] I'm
representing the Eugene Wright

01:42:35.260 --> 01:42:37.990
Science and Technology Academy
in Chelsea, Massachusetts

01:42:37.990 --> 01:42:39.880
and Northeastern University.

01:42:39.880 --> 01:42:43.630
My question is you talked about
a plethora of transmission

01:42:43.630 --> 01:42:47.200
factors, both environmental
and genetic, in your respected

01:42:47.200 --> 01:42:48.920
epidemics.

01:42:48.920 --> 01:42:51.610
What my question is is
that is there any research

01:42:51.610 --> 01:42:54.220
or is there any research
you're aware of being

01:42:54.220 --> 01:42:58.720
done on the epigenomic factors
in these disease transmissions?

01:42:58.720 --> 01:42:59.510
Thank you.

01:42:59.510 --> 01:43:00.010
- Thank you.

01:43:00.010 --> 01:43:00.958
The next one?

01:43:06.172 --> 01:43:09.190
- If Zika virus
creates complications

01:43:09.190 --> 01:43:12.910
for pregnant women and birth
defects for their children,

01:43:12.910 --> 01:43:19.985
what are some ways mothers can
prevent this from happening?

01:43:19.985 --> 01:43:21.350
- OK.

01:43:21.350 --> 01:43:23.450
One more and then I'll
go to the answers.

01:43:23.450 --> 01:43:25.160
- My name is Ethel Jackson.

01:43:25.160 --> 01:43:28.970
And I just have to say
I've had a 40-year career

01:43:28.970 --> 01:43:32.210
in molecular
genetics of microbes

01:43:32.210 --> 01:43:34.700
in university and in
industrial settings.

01:43:34.700 --> 01:43:39.110
And I am awed and humbled by
what I've heard from this panel

01:43:39.110 --> 01:43:40.130
this morning.

01:43:40.130 --> 01:43:42.560
I congratulate
you and thank you.

01:43:42.560 --> 01:43:44.390
A quick question
though going forward

01:43:44.390 --> 01:43:47.840
about how technology might help.

01:43:47.840 --> 01:43:51.920
Is there work ongoing
to develop vaccines

01:43:51.920 --> 01:43:53.900
against Ebola and Zika?

01:43:53.900 --> 01:43:58.100
Do you think that is
a promising approach,

01:43:58.100 --> 01:44:02.330
or do you think that it
will be in the future solely

01:44:02.330 --> 01:44:06.020
up to public health
and epidemiology

01:44:06.020 --> 01:44:08.700
to protect us from
these diseases?

01:44:08.700 --> 01:44:09.380
- Thank you.

01:44:09.380 --> 01:44:11.920
So, folks, we have three
minutes when you [INAUDIBLE]----

01:44:11.920 --> 01:44:14.980
if you want to answer.

01:44:14.980 --> 01:44:20.460
- Well, as far as the epigenomic
factors involving transmission

01:44:20.460 --> 01:44:24.980
of disease is concerned, there
may be some work out there,

01:44:24.980 --> 01:44:28.110
but not that I am aware of.

01:44:28.110 --> 01:44:30.450
But it's very possible that
there is work going on.

01:44:30.450 --> 01:44:34.640
But often, I think, in the
context in which we're working,

01:44:34.640 --> 01:44:38.540
the context of outbreak, it's
very difficult at that time

01:44:38.540 --> 01:44:42.020
to sit down and then design an
experiment that will actually

01:44:42.020 --> 01:44:44.000
take into account all of this--

01:44:44.000 --> 01:44:46.970
I mean, investigate
the epigenomic--

01:44:46.970 --> 01:44:49.827
especially in the context of
an Ebola or Lassa outbreak.

01:44:49.827 --> 01:44:52.160
But it's very possible that
there is some work out there

01:44:52.160 --> 01:44:54.366
that I'm not aware of.

01:44:54.366 --> 01:44:56.240
- I'll respond to the
question about vaccines

01:44:56.240 --> 01:44:57.990
and therapeutics.

01:44:57.990 --> 01:45:00.520
Certainly, there have
been major strides

01:45:00.520 --> 01:45:03.760
in the last several years
with vaccines of therapeutics

01:45:03.760 --> 01:45:05.230
with regard to Ebola.

01:45:05.230 --> 01:45:09.280
And certainly there are
candidates out there.

01:45:09.280 --> 01:45:11.702
We also believe that the
people that we're working with

01:45:11.702 --> 01:45:13.660
may have very, very
interesting antibodies that

01:45:13.660 --> 01:45:15.820
are developed long over time.

01:45:15.820 --> 01:45:18.610
But the bigger question
that you asked was,

01:45:18.610 --> 01:45:20.680
do you think that this
is the way forward?

01:45:20.680 --> 01:45:22.930
And we had a long discussion
about this yesterday.

01:45:22.930 --> 01:45:26.350
And I think that while
vaccines and therapeutics are

01:45:26.350 --> 01:45:29.050
very important and something
that does need to be pursued,

01:45:29.050 --> 01:45:32.140
the real issue is
lack of infrastructure

01:45:32.140 --> 01:45:34.330
in these countries and
the ability of the people

01:45:34.330 --> 01:45:37.570
in these countries to be able
to have infrastructure required

01:45:37.570 --> 01:45:39.790
to have adequate disease
reporting so that people

01:45:39.790 --> 01:45:42.730
understand what's going on
in real time in the places

01:45:42.730 --> 01:45:44.830
where you need to
understand it most, and have

01:45:44.830 --> 01:45:48.670
the well-trained and equipped
people on the ground who have

01:45:48.670 --> 01:45:51.030
the ability to respond quickly.

01:45:51.030 --> 01:45:53.260
And if you have those
things, then the vaccines

01:45:53.260 --> 01:45:56.120
and therapeutics are a
nice secondary response,

01:45:56.120 --> 01:45:59.070
but they are not the primary
thing that will save us.

01:45:59.070 --> 01:45:59.570
- OK.

01:45:59.570 --> 01:46:00.070
- Thank you.

01:46:00.070 --> 01:46:01.030
Celina?

01:46:01.030 --> 01:46:02.020
- OK.

01:46:02.020 --> 01:46:06.120
Prevention-- I think that from
now we have recommendations

01:46:06.120 --> 01:46:07.200
for pregnant women.

01:46:07.200 --> 01:46:11.160
If you go to a CDC--

01:46:11.160 --> 01:46:12.390
I mean, all sites.

01:46:12.390 --> 01:46:14.610
I mean, there are preventions.

01:46:14.610 --> 01:46:17.160
And you should not--

01:46:17.160 --> 01:46:19.170
if you want to be--

01:46:19.170 --> 01:46:21.750
if you're planning
to be pregnant,

01:46:21.750 --> 01:46:25.800
you shouldn't visit areas
with the virus circulation.

01:46:25.800 --> 01:46:28.960
Without a vaccine,
that's what we can do.

01:46:28.960 --> 01:46:34.170
Think about transmission by
vector-borne, by a vector,

01:46:34.170 --> 01:46:37.840
by a mosquito, and by
sexual transmission.

01:46:37.840 --> 01:46:41.790
So if you have a partner
that visits an endemic area--

01:46:41.790 --> 01:46:47.700
so, you have to have safe sex
for six months, whatever--

01:46:47.700 --> 01:46:49.530
we don't know
exactly for how long.

01:46:49.530 --> 01:46:52.360
[LAUGHTER]

01:46:52.360 --> 01:46:56.250
So, I think that vaccine
is something to look for

01:46:56.250 --> 01:47:01.800
and to see how transmission
is going to progress

01:47:01.800 --> 01:47:04.110
during the following years.

01:47:04.110 --> 01:47:04.890
- Thank you.

01:47:04.890 --> 01:47:07.200
So, I want to thank
all the speakers

01:47:07.200 --> 01:47:09.580
because we are right on time.

01:47:09.580 --> 01:47:12.060
So we're not going to get a
red card from the organizers.

01:47:12.060 --> 01:47:12.720
Look at that.

